window.ITEMS_UNIT6=[{"problem_id":"unit06-0001","original_source":"cpm-8-33","source_lesson":"8.1.3","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"1","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 1: Solving Quadratics by Factoring","source_type":"Review/Preview","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Builds toward Zero Product Property by solving products of factors equal to zero; solving objective.","question_html":"<article class=\"problem\" id=\"8-33\">\n<h3>8-33.</h3>\n<div class=\"meta\"><span class=\"tag\">Review/Preview</span><span>Sorted to Unit 6, Section 1: Solving Quadratics by Factoring</span></div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Builds toward the zero product property by solving linear factors and products of factors equal to zero.</div>\n<p>Solve each equation below for $x$. Check each solution.</p>\n<div class=\"three-col\">\n<ol class=\"lower-alpha\"><li>$2x-10=0$</li><li>$x+6=0$</li></ol>\n<ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"3\"><li>$(2x-10)(x+6)=0$</li><li>$4x+1=0$</li></ol>\n<ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"5\"><li>$x-8=0$</li><li>$(4x+1)(x-8)=0$</li></ol>\n</div>\n</article>"},{"problem_id":"unit06-0002","original_source":"cpm-8-66","source_lesson":"8.2.2","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"1","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 1: Solving Quadratics by Factoring","source_type":"Lesson","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Develops the Zero Product Property as the basis for solving factored quadratic equations.","question_html":"<section class=\"problem\" id=\"8-66\">\n<h2>8-66</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Lesson</span> Sorted to Unit 6, Section 1: Solving Quadratics by Factoring</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Develops the Zero Product Property as the reason factored quadratic equations can be solved by setting factors equal to zero.</div>\n<div><p>ZERO PRODUCT PROPERTY</p><p>The equation you wrote in part (c) of problem 8-65 is called a quadratic equation. To solve it, you need to examine what you know about zero.\u00a0 Study the special properties of zero below.</p><p>Nathan, Sonia, and Gaston are playing a game where Nathan and Sonia each think of a number and then give Gaston a clue about their numbers.\u00a0 Using the clue, Gaston must tell them everything that he knows about their numbers.</p><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" type=\"a\"><li><p>Nathan and Sonia\u2019s first clue for Gaston is that when you multiply their numbers together, the result is zero. What conclusion can Gaston make?\u00a0</p></li><li><p>Disappointed that Gaston came so close to figuring out their numbers, Nathan and Sonia invite Nadia over to make things harder. Nathan, Sonia, and Nadia all think of secret numbers. This time Gaston is told that when their <em>three </em>secret numbers are multiplied together, the answer is zero. What can Gaston conclude this time?</p></li><li><p>Does it matter how many numbers are multiplied?\u00a0 If the product is zero, what do you know about one of the numbers?\u00a0 This property is called the Zero Product Property.\u00a0 With the class, write a description of this property in your Learning Log.\u00a0 Title this entry \u201cZero Product Property\u201d and include today\u2019s date.</p></li></ol></div>\n</section>"},{"problem_id":"unit06-0003","original_source":"cpm-8-67","source_lesson":"8.2.2","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"1","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 1: Solving Quadratics by Factoring","source_type":"Lesson","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Uses factoring and ZPP to solve a quadratic equation and interpret roots.","question_html":"<section class=\"problem\" id=\"8-67\">\n<h2>8-67</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Lesson</span> Sorted to Unit 6, Section 1: Solving Quadratics by Factoring</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Uses factoring and the Zero Product Property to solve a quadratic equation and interpret its roots as x-intercepts.</div>\n<div><p> Let\u2019s investigate how can you use the Zero Product Property to help you solve the quadratic equation\u00a0$2x^2+5x-12=0$ from part (d) of problem 8-65? \t</p><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" type=\"a\"><li><p>Examine the quadratic equation.\u00a0 Is there a product that equals zero?\u00a0 If not, how can you rewrite the quadratic expression as a product?\u00a0</p></li><li><p>Now that the equation is written as a product of factors equaling zero, you can use the Zero Product Property to solve it.\u00a0 Since you know that one of the factors must be zero, you can set up two simpler equations to help you solve for <em>$x$</em>.\u00a0 Use one factor at a time and determine what <em>$x\\text{-value}$</em> makes it equal to zero.\u00a0\u00a0</p></li><li><p>What do these solutions represent?\u00a0 What do they tell you?\u00a0</p></li><li><p>You now know the roots (also called the zeros) of\u00a0<em>$y=2x^2+5x-12$</em><em></em>.\u00a0Use the roots to find the <em>$x$</em>-intercepts of the graph of the parabola <em>$y=2x^2+5x-12$</em>. Then sketch a graph of the parabola.<em></em><em></em><em></em><em></em></p></li></ol></div>\n</section>"},{"problem_id":"unit06-0004","original_source":"cpm-8-70","source_lesson":"8.2.2","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"1","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 1: Solving Quadratics by Factoring","source_type":"Review/Preview","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Compares product and sum equations to clarify when ZPP applies.","question_html":"<section class=\"problem\" id=\"8-70\">\n<h2>8-70</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Review/Preview</span> Sorted to Unit 6, Section 1: Solving Quadratics by Factoring</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Compares a product equation with a sum equation to clarify when the Zero Product Property applies.</div>\n<div><p>Compare the two equations below.\u00a0\u00a0</p><p>$\\left(x+2\\right)\\left(x-1\\right)=0$ and $\\left(x+2\\right)+\\left(x-1\\right)=0$</p><div><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" type=\"a\"><li><p>How are the equations different?</p></li></ol></div><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"2\" type=\"a\"><li><p>Solve both equations.</p></li></ol></div></div></div>\n</section>"},{"problem_id":"unit06-0005","original_source":"cpm-8-71","source_lesson":"8.2.2","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"1","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 1: Solving Quadratics by Factoring","source_type":"Review/Preview","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Solves factored quadratic equations using the Zero Product Property.","question_html":"<section class=\"problem\" id=\"8-71\">\n<h2>8-71</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Review/Preview</span> Sorted to Unit 6, Section 1: Solving Quadratics by Factoring</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Solves factored quadratic equations using the Zero Product Property.</div>\n<div><p>For each equation below, solve for <em>$x$</em>.\u00a0\u00a0</p><div><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" type=\"a\"><li><p>$\\left(x-2\\right)\\left(x+8\\right)=0$\u00a0</p></li></ol></div><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"2\" type=\"a\"><li><p>$\\left(3x-9\\right)\\left(x-1\\right)=0$\u00a0</p></li></ol></div></div><div><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"3\" type=\"a\"><li><p>$\\left(x+10\\right)\\left(2x-5\\right)=0$\u00a0</p></li></ol></div><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"4\" type=\"a\"><li><p>$\\left(x-7\\right)^2=0$\u00a0</p></li></ol></div></div></div>\n</section>"},{"problem_id":"unit06-0006","original_source":"cpm-8-83","source_lesson":"8.2.3","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"1","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 1: Solving Quadratics by Factoring","source_type":"Review/Preview","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Finds roots using factoring and the Zero Product Property.","question_html":"<section class=\"problem\" id=\"8-83\">\n<h2>8-83</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Review/Preview</span> Sorted to Unit 6, Section 1: Solving Quadratics by Factoring</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Finds polynomial roots using factoring and the Zero Product Property.</div>\n<div><p>Use the Zero Product Property to find the roots of the polynomials below.</p>\n<div><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" type=\"a\"><li><p>$3x^2-7x+4$</p></li></ol></div><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"2\" type=\"a\"><li><p>$x^2+6x$</p></li></ol></div><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"3\" type=\"a\"><li><p>$(x+5)(-2x+3)$</p></li></ol></div></div></div>\n</section>"},{"problem_id":"unit06-0007","original_source":"cpm-8-85","source_lesson":"8.2.3","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"1","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 1: Solving Quadratics by Factoring","source_type":"Review/Preview","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Solves factored and factorable quadratic equations using ZPP.","question_html":"<section class=\"problem\" id=\"8-85\">\n<h2>8-85</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Review/Preview</span> Sorted to Unit 6, Section 1: Solving Quadratics by Factoring</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Solves factored and factorable quadratic equations using the Zero Product Property.</div>\n<div><p>Solve the equations below for <em>$x$</em>. Check your solutions.</p>\n<div><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" type=\"a\"><li><p>$(6x-18)(3x+2)=0$</p></li></ol></div><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"2\" type=\"a\"><li><p>$x^2-7x+10=0$</p></li></ol></div></div>\n<div><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"3\" type=\"a\"><li><p>$2x^2+2x-12=0$</p></li></ol></div><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"4\" type=\"a\"><li><p>$4x^2-1=0$</p></li></ol></div></div></div>\n</section>"},{"problem_id":"unit06-0008","original_source":"cpm-8-95","source_lesson":"8.2.4","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"1","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 1: Solving Quadratics by Factoring","source_type":"Review/Preview","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Solves factorable quadratic equations and checks solutions.","question_html":"<section class=\"problem\" id=\"8-95\">\n<h2>8-95</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Review/Preview</span> Sorted to Unit 6, Section 1: Solving Quadratics by Factoring</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Solves factorable quadratic equations and checks solutions.</div>\n<div><p>Solve the equations below for <em>$x$</em>. Check your solutions.</p>\n<div class=\"two-col\"><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" type=\"a\"><li><p>$x^2+6x-40=0$</p></li></ol></div><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"2\" type=\"a\"><li><p>$2x^2+13x-24=0$</p></li></ol></div></div></div>\n</section>"},{"problem_id":"unit06-0009","original_source":"cpm-8-107","source_lesson":"8.2.5","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"1","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 1: Solving Quadratics by Factoring","source_type":"Review/Preview","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Solves factored and factorable quadratic equations using factoring and ZPP.","question_html":"<section class=\"problem\" id=\"8-107\">\n<h2>8-107</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Review/Preview</span> Sorted to Unit 6, Section 1: Solving Quadratics by Factoring</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Solves factored and factorable quadratic equations using factoring and the Zero Product Property.</div>\n<p>Use factoring and the Zero Product Property to solve each equation.</p>\n<div class=\"two-col\"><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" type=\"a\"><li><p>$(x-4)(2x+1)=0$</p></li></ol></div><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"2\" type=\"a\"><li><p>$x^2+5x+6=0$</p></li></ol></div></div>\n<div class=\"two-col\"><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"3\" type=\"a\"><li><p>$x(2x-5)=0$</p></li></ol></div><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"4\" type=\"a\"><li><p>$x^2+4x=0$</p></li></ol></div></div>\n</section>"},{"problem_id":"unit06-0010","original_source":"cpm-CL8-112","source_lesson":"Chapter 8 Closure","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"1","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 1: Solving Quadratics by Factoring","source_type":"Closure","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Factors quadratics and uses the Zero Product Property to find roots.","question_html":"<div class=\"card\" id=\"CL8112\">\n<div class=\"problem-title\">CL 8-112</div>\n<p>Factor and use the Zero Product Property to find the roots of the following quadratic equations.</p>\n<div class=\"grid-2\">\n<ol type=\"a\"><li>$0=x^2-7x+12$</li></ol>\n<ol start=\"2\" type=\"a\"><li>$0=6x^2-23x+20$</li></ol>\n<ol start=\"3\" type=\"a\"><li>$0=x^2-9$</li></ol>\n<ol start=\"4\" type=\"a\"><li>$0=x^2+12x+36$</li></ol>\n</div>\n</div>"},{"problem_id":"unit06-0011","original_source":"cpm-9-1","source_lesson":"9.1.1","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"1","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 1: Solving by Factoring","source_type":"Lesson","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Solves quadratic equations using the Zero Product Property.","question_html":"<section class=\"problem\" id=\"9-1\">\n<h2>9-1</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Lesson</span> Sorted to Unit 6, Section 1: Solving Quadratics by Factoring</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Solves quadratic equations by rewriting as zero-product equations and applying the Zero Product Property.</div>\n<div><p>Use the Zero Product Property to solve the quadratic equations below.</p>\n<div class=\"three-col\">\n<div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" type=\"a\"><li><p>$9=3x^2+4x-6$</p></li></ol></div>\n<div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"2\" type=\"a\"><li><p>$0=3(x-5)(2x+3)$</p></li></ol></div>\n<div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"3\" type=\"a\"><li><p>$x^2+6x=0$</p></li></ol></div>\n</div></div>\n</section>"},{"problem_id":"unit06-0012","original_source":"cpm-9-2","source_lesson":"9.1.1","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"1","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 1: Solving by Factoring","source_type":"Lesson","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Graphing technology is used only to verify factoring solutions; classify by the algebraic method.","question_html":"<section class=\"problem\" id=\"9-2\">\n<h2>9-2</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Lesson</span> Sorted to Unit 6, Section 2: Solving Quadratics with Graphs and Square Roots</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Uses graphing technology to verify solutions of quadratic equations by interpreting graphs and tables.</div>\n<div><p>Let\u2019s use your calculator to verify your solutions to the original equations in problem 9-1, before you started rewriting them, or use the <a class=\"etool-link\" href=\"https://www.desmos.com/calculator/dsbrvomolb\" rel=\"noopener\" target=\"_blank\">9-2 Student eTool</a>.</p>\n<div class=\"two-col\"><div>\n<ol class=\"lower-alpha\" type=\"a\">\n<li><p>Graph <em>$y=3x^2+4x-6$</em> with your graphing calculator. Where on the graph would you look to verify your solution to part (a) of problem 9-1?</p></li>\n<li><p>Where in the table on your graphing calculator would you look to verify your solution to part (a) of problem 9-1?</p></li>\n<li><p>Use your graphing calculator to verify your solutions to the other equations in problem 9-1.</p></li>\n</ol>\n</div><div><img alt=\"Graph of y equals 3x squared plus 4x minus 6 used to verify solutions by graphing.\" class=\"medium-img\" src=\"assets/9-2.png\"/></div></div></div>\n</section>","resources":[{"label":"9-2 Student eTool","href":"https://www.desmos.com/calculator/dsbrvomolb"}]},{"problem_id":"unit06-0013","original_source":"cpm-9-17","source_lesson":"9.1.2","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"1","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 1: Solving by Factoring","source_type":"Review/Preview","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Solves quadratic equations by factoring and Zero Product Property.","question_html":"<section class=\"problem\" id=\"9-17\">\n<h2>9-17</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Review/Preview</span> Sorted to Unit 6, Section 1: Solving Quadratics by Factoring</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Solves quadratic equations by factoring and using the Zero Product Property.</div>\n<div><p>Solve the following quadratic equations by factoring and using the Zero Product Property. Be sure to check your solutions.</p>\n<ol class=\"lower-alpha\" type=\"a\">\n<li><p>$x^2-13x+42=0$</p></li>\n<li><p>$0=3x^2+10x-8$</p></li>\n<li><p>$2x^2-10x=0$</p></li>\n<li><p>$4x^2+8x-60=0$</p></li>\n</ol></div>\n</section>"},{"problem_id":"unit06-0014","original_source":"cpm-9-27","source_lesson":"9.1.3","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"1","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 1: Solving by Factoring","source_type":"Review/Preview","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Solves quadratic equations by factoring and ZPP.","question_html":"<section class=\"problem\" id=\"9-27\">\n<h2>9-27</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Review/Preview</span> Sorted to Unit 6, Section 1: Solving Quadratics by Factoring</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Solves quadratic equations by factoring and using the Zero Product Property.</div>\n<div><p>Solve the following quadratic equations by factoring and using the Zero Product Property. Then check your solutions.</p>\n<div class=\"two-col\">\n<div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" type=\"a\"><li><p>$x^2-10x+25=0$</p></li></ol></div>\n<div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"2\" type=\"a\"><li><p>$0=3x^2+17x-6$</p></li></ol></div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"two-col\">\n<div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"3\" type=\"a\"><li><p>$3x^2-2x=5$</p></li></ol></div>\n<div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"4\" type=\"a\"><li><p>$16x^2-9=0$</p></li></ol></div>\n</div></div>\n</section>"},{"problem_id":"unit06-0015","original_source":"cpm-9-36","source_lesson":"9.1.4","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"1","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 1: Solving by Factoring","source_type":"Lesson","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Focuses on valid use of the Zero Product Property after rewriting equation to zero.","question_html":"<section class=\"problem\" id=\"9-36\">\n<h2>9-36</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Lesson</span> Sorted to Unit 6, Section 1: Solving Quadratics by Factoring</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Identifies why the Zero Product Property only applies after rewriting an equation so one side equals zero.</div>\n<div><p>While solving $(x-5)(x+2)=-6$, Kyle decided that $x$ must equal $5$ or $-2$. \u201cNot so fast!\u201d exclaimed Stanton, \u201cThe product does not equal zero. We need to change the equation first.\u201d</p>\n<ol class=\"lower-alpha\" type=\"a\">\n<li><p>What is Stanton talking about?</p></li>\n<li><p>How can the equation be rewritten? Discuss this with your team and use your algebraic tools to rewrite the equation so that it can be solved.</p></li>\n<li><p>Solve the resulting equation from part (b) for $x$.</p></li>\n<li><p>Use the graph and table of $y=(x-5)(x+2)$ on your graphing calculator to check your solution. See whether Kyle's solution matches the solution in part (c).</p></li>\n</ol></div>\n</section>"},{"problem_id":"unit06-0016","original_source":"cpm-CL9-125b","source_lesson":"Chapter 9 Closure","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"1","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 1: Solving by Factoring","source_type":"Closure","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Explicitly solved by factoring.","question_html":"<div class=\"card\" id=\"CL9125\">\n<div class=\"problem-title\">CL 9-125</div>\n<p>Solve each quadratic equation using the specified method.</p>\n<div class=\"grid-2\">\n<ol type=\"a\"><li><span class=\"method\">The Quadratic Formula</span><br/>$0=3x^2+4x-7$</li></ol>\n<ol start=\"2\" type=\"a\"><li><span class=\"method\">Factoring</span><br/>$x^2-3x-18=0$</li></ol>\n<ol start=\"3\" type=\"a\"><li><span class=\"method\">Completing the square</span><br/>$x^2+4x+1=0$</li></ol>\n<ol start=\"4\" type=\"a\"><li><span class=\"method\">Using a graph</span><br/>$2x^2+5x-12=0$</li></ol>\n</div>\n</div>"},{"problem_id":"unit06-0017","original_source":"cpm-8-77","source_lesson":"8.2.3","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"2","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 2: Solving Quadratics with Graphs and Square Roots","source_type":"Lesson","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Introduces non-factorable roots and graph/table estimation of solutions.","question_html":"<section class=\"problem\" id=\"8-77\">\n<h2>8-77</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Lesson</span> Sorted to Unit 6, Section 2: Solving Quadratics with Graphs and Square Roots</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Uses calculator graphs and tables to estimate roots when factoring does not work cleanly.</div>\n<div><p>Use the Zero Product Property to find the roots of <em>$x^2-3x-7=y$</em>.</p>\n<ol class=\"lower-alpha\" type=\"a\"><li><p>What happened? What does this result tell you about the roots?</p></li><li><p>Use your graphing calculator to display the graph of <em>$y=x^2-3x-7$</em>. Did the graph confirm your answer to part (a)? Estimate the roots using the graph.</p></li><li><p>How could you estimate the roots by looking at the table on your graphing calculator?</p></li></ol></div>\n</section>"},{"problem_id":"unit06-0018","original_source":"cpm-8-78","source_lesson":"8.2.3","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"2","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 2: Solving Quadratics with Graphs and Square Roots","source_type":"Lesson","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Estimates x-intercepts using graphs and tables.","question_html":"<section class=\"problem\" id=\"8-78\">\n<h2>8-78</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Lesson</span> Sorted to Unit 6, Section 2: Solving Quadratics with Graphs and Square Roots</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Estimates x-intercepts of quadratic functions using graph and table representations.</div>\n<div><p>Estimate the <em>$x$-intercepts</em> of the following parabolas by using the graph and table on your graphing calculator.</p>\n<div><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" type=\"a\"><li><p>$-x^2+3x+6=y$</p></li></ol></div><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"2\" type=\"a\"><li><p>$f(x)=4x^2+16x+16$</p></li></ol></div></div>\n<div><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"3\" type=\"a\"><li><p>$y=x^2+5x+1$</p></li></ol></div><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"4\" type=\"a\"><li><p>$y=x^2-5x+9$</p></li></ol></div></div></div>\n</section>"},{"problem_id":"unit06-0019","original_source":"cpm-8-82","source_lesson":"8.2.3","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"2","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 2: Solving Quadratics with Graphs and Square Roots","source_type":"Lesson","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Summarizes strategies for finding x-intercepts, including graphs and square-root methods.","question_html":"<section class=\"problem\" id=\"8-82\">\n<h2>8-82</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Lesson</span> Sorted to Unit 6, Section 2: Solving Quadratics with Graphs and Square Roots</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Summarizes multiple strategies for finding x-intercepts of quadratic equations.</div>\n<div><p>In your Learning Log, describe the different strategies for finding the <em>$x$</em>-intercepts in a quadratic equation. Title this entry \u201cStrategies for Finding <em>x</em>-Intercepts\u201d and include today\u2019s date.</p></div>\n</section>"},{"problem_id":"unit06-0020","original_source":"cpm-8-94","source_lesson":"8.2.4","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"2","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 2: Solving Quadratics with Graphs and Square Roots","source_type":"Review/Preview","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Estimates non-integer zeros from a graph and notes factoring/ZPP is inefficient.","question_html":"<section class=\"problem\" id=\"8-94\">\n<h2>8-94</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Review/Preview</span> Sorted to Unit 6, Section 2: Solving Quadratics with Graphs and Square Roots</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Estimates non-integer zeros from a graph and recognizes when simple factoring/ZPP is not efficient.</div>\n<div><div class=\"two-col\"><div><p>Examine the graph of <em>$y=2x^2+2x-1$</em> at right.</p>\n<ol class=\"lower-alpha\" type=\"a\"><li><p>Estimate the zeros of <em>$y=2x^2+2x-1$</em> from the graph.</p></li><li><p>What happens if you try to use the Zero Product Property to find the roots of $2x^2+2x-1=0$?</p></li></ol></div><div><img alt=\"Graph of y equals 2x squared plus 2x minus 1 with two x-intercepts that are not integers.\" class=\"medium-img\" src=\"assets/8-94.png\"/></div></div></div>\n</section>"},{"problem_id":"unit06-0021","original_source":"cpm-9-3","source_lesson":"9.1.1","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"2","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 2: Solving Quadratics by Completing the Square","source_type":"Lesson","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Non-factorable quadratic solved exactly by completing the square; graphing estimate supports but does not dominate.","question_html":"<section class=\"problem\" id=\"9-3\">\n<h2>9-3</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Lesson</span> Sorted to Unit 6, Section 4: Completing the Square</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Uses completing the square with tiles and graphing estimates to solve a non-factorable quadratic exactly.</div>\n<div><p>Janelle\u2019s team was trying to solve <em>$x^2-6x-1=0$</em>.</p>\n<p>Janelle suggested using the Zero Product Property.</p>\n<p>Kira said, <em>\u201cThis quadratic is not factorable. So it doesn\u2019t have a solution!\u201d</em></p>\n<ol class=\"lower-alpha\" type=\"a\">\n<li><p>Is Kira correct? How do you know?</p>\n<p><em>\u201cI know. Let\u2019s use the graphing calculator and see if there are solutions.\u201d</em> Katelyn said.</p></li>\n<li><p>What did Katelyn mean? If you have not already done so, estimate the solution.</p>\n<p><em>\u201cBut,\u201d</em> Janelle said, <em>\u201cthe teacher said to get an exact solution. Let\u2019s complete the square to help us solve. Here\u2019s what the equation would look like.\u201d</em></p>\n<img alt=\"Algebra-tile equation mat for x squared minus 6x minus 1 with tile key.\" class=\"wide-img\" src=\"assets/9-3.png\"/>\n<p>Erika contributed, <em>\u201cOh, I see. Now we can add $-8$ unit tiles to each side to complete the square.\u201d</em></p>\n<p><em>\u201cI\u2019m not so sure,\u201d</em> said Katelyn. <em>\u201cThat would give us $-9$ in the corner. Is that right?\u201d</em></p></li>\n<li><p>What do you think the team\u2019s next legal tile move should be?</p></li>\n<li><p>Complete the square, and solve. Does your solution match your estimate from part (b)?</p></li>\n<li><p>To make sense of the <em>$x$</em>-intercepts in part (d), you probably wrote your solution as a decimal. Square roots that are not perfect squares are irrational numbers: they are numbers that cannot be written as a fraction of integers. Irrational numbers cannot be written exactly as a decimal. The decimals continue infinitely and never go into a repeating pattern.</p>\n<p>When you write a square root as a decimal you have to round, so it is called <strong>approximate decimal form</strong>. When you use the square root symbol, you are using <strong>exact form</strong> or <strong>radical form</strong>.</p>\n<p>Build the equation <em>$x^2+4x-5=-2$</em> with algebra tiles. Use Kira\u2019s method to complete the square and solve. Write your answer in both exact form and approximate decimal form.</p></li>\n<li><p>Check your answer to part (e) by graphing.</p></li>\n</ol></div>\n</section>"},{"problem_id":"unit06-0022","original_source":"cpm-9-4","source_lesson":"9.1.1","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"2","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 2: Solving Quadratics by Completing the Square","source_type":"Lesson","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Solves quadratic equations by completing the square with generic rectangles.","question_html":"<section class=\"problem\" id=\"9-4\">\n<h2>9-4</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Lesson</span> Sorted to Unit 6, Section 4: Completing the Square</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Solves quadratic equations by completing the square, including after simplifying a leading coefficient.</div>\n<div><p>Solve the following equations using Kira\u2019s method. Use generic rectangles to help you complete the square.</p>\n<div class=\"two-col\"><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" type=\"a\"><li><p>$x^2-2x-3=1$</p></li></ol></div><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"2\" type=\"a\"><li><p>$8x^2+40x=238$</p></li></ol></div></div></div>\n</section>"},{"problem_id":"unit06-0023","original_source":"cpm-9-5","source_lesson":"9.1.1","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"2","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 2: Solving Quadratics by Completing the Square","source_type":"Lesson","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Calculator graphing is used only to verify completing-the-square solutions.","question_html":"<section class=\"problem\" id=\"9-5\">\n<h2>9-5</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Lesson</span> Sorted to Unit 6, Section 2: Solving Quadratics with Graphs and Square Roots</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Verifies solutions to quadratic equations using graphing technology.</div>\n<div><p>Use your graphing calculator to verify your solutions to the original equations in problem 9-4.</p></div>\n</section>"},{"problem_id":"unit06-0024","original_source":"cpm-9-6","source_lesson":"9.1.1","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"2","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 2: Solving Quadratics by Completing the Square","source_type":"Review/Preview","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Generalized completing-the-square solving process.","question_html":"<section class=\"problem\" id=\"9-6\">\n<h2>9-6</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Review/Preview</span> Sorted to Unit 6, Section 4: Completing the Square</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Rewrites and solves quadratic equations using a generalized completing-the-square process.</div>\n<div><p>Use your generalized process of completing the square to rewrite and solve each quadratic equation below.</p>\n<div class=\"two-col\"><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" type=\"a\"><li><p>$w^2+28w+52=0$</p></li></ol></div><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"2\" type=\"a\"><li><p>$x^2+5x+4=0$</p></li></ol></div></div>\n<div class=\"two-col\"><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"3\" type=\"a\"><li><p>$k^2-16k-17=0$</p></li></ol></div><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"4\" type=\"a\"><li><p>$z^2-1000z+60775=0$</p></li></ol></div></div></div>\n</section>"},{"problem_id":"unit06-0025","original_source":"cpm-9-12","source_lesson":"9.1.2","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"2","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 2: Solving Quadratics by Completing the Square","source_type":"Lesson","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Writes equations in perfect-square form and determines the number of real solutions from that structure.","question_html":"<section class=\"problem\" id=\"9-12\">\n<h2>9-12</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Lesson</span> Sorted to Unit 6, Section 4: Completing the Square</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Writes quadratic equations in perfect-square form and determines the number of real solutions from that structure.</div>\n<div><p>A quadratic equation can be rewritten in <span class=\"term\">perfect square form</span>, $(ax+b)^2=c$, by completing the square.</p>\n<p>Write the following equations in perfect square form. Then determine the number of solutions for each quadratic equation. You do not need to actually solve the equations.</p>\n<p>Explain how you can quickly determine how many solutions a quadratic equation has once it is written in perfect square form.</p>\n<div class=\"two-col\">\n<div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" type=\"a\"><li><p>$x^2-6x+10=3$</p></li></ol></div>\n<div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"2\" type=\"a\"><li><p>$m^2+12m+37=0$</p></li></ol></div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"two-col\">\n<div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"3\" type=\"a\"><li><p>$4p^2+36p=-81$</p></li></ol></div>\n<div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"4\" type=\"a\"><li><p>$k^2-3k+9=0$</p></li></ol></div>\n</div></div>\n</section>"},{"problem_id":"unit06-0026","original_source":"cpm-9-19","source_lesson":"9.1.2","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"2","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 2: Solving Quadratics by Completing the Square","source_type":"Review/Preview","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Analyzes 0, 1, and 2 real solutions through graph behavior before formal discriminant analysis.","question_html":"<section class=\"problem\" id=\"9-19\">\n<h2>9-19</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Review/Preview</span> Sorted to Unit 6, Section 2: Solving Quadratics with Graphs and Square Roots</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Connects the number of real quadratic solutions to whether a parabola crosses the x-axis zero, one, or two times.</div>\n<div><p>Does a quadratic equation always have two real solutions? That is, does a parabola always intersect the $x$-axis twice? <a class=\"etool-link\" href=\"https://www.desmos.com/calculator/f8khly5lnz\" rel=\"noopener\" target=\"_blank\">9-19 HW eTool</a></p>\n<ol class=\"lower-alpha\" type=\"a\">\n<li><p>If possible, draw an example of a parabola that only intersects the $x$-axis once.</p></li>\n<li><p>What does it mean if the quadratic equation has no solution? Draw a possible parabola that would cause this to happen.</p></li>\n</ol></div>\n</section>","resources":[{"label":"9-19 HW eTool","href":"https://www.desmos.com/calculator/f8khly5lnz"}]},{"problem_id":"unit06-0027","original_source":"cpm-9-21","source_lesson":"9.1.2","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"2","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 2: Solving Quadratics by Completing the Square","source_type":"Review/Preview","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Completes the square to write graphing form and identify vertices.","question_html":"<section class=\"problem\" id=\"9-21\">\n<h2>9-21</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Review/Preview</span> Sorted to Unit 6, Section 4: Completing the Square</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Rewrites quadratics in graphing form by completing the square and identifies the vertex as a minimum.</div>\n<div><p>For each quadratic function below, use the idea of completing the square to write it in graphing form. Then state the vertex of each parabola.</p>\n<div class=\"two-col\">\n<div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" type=\"a\"><li><p>$f(x)=x^2+4x+5$</p></li></ol></div>\n<div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"2\" type=\"a\"><li><p>$f(x)=x^2-6x$</p></li></ol></div>\n</div>\n<ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"3\" type=\"a\">\n<li><p>In both graphs, does the vertex represent the maximum or minimum value of the parabola?</p></li>\n</ol></div>\n</section>"},{"problem_id":"unit06-0028","original_source":"cpm-CL9-125c","source_lesson":"Chapter 9 Closure","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"2","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 2: Solving Quadratics by Completing the Square","source_type":"Closure","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Explicitly solved by completing the square.","question_html":"<div class=\"card\" id=\"CL9125\">\n<div class=\"problem-title\">CL 9-125</div>\n<p>Solve each quadratic equation using the specified method.</p>\n<div class=\"grid-2\">\n<ol type=\"a\"><li><span class=\"method\">The Quadratic Formula</span><br/>$0=3x^2+4x-7$</li></ol>\n<ol start=\"2\" type=\"a\"><li><span class=\"method\">Factoring</span><br/>$x^2-3x-18=0$</li></ol>\n<ol start=\"3\" type=\"a\"><li><span class=\"method\">Completing the square</span><br/>$x^2+4x+1=0$</li></ol>\n<ol start=\"4\" type=\"a\"><li><span class=\"method\">Using a graph</span><br/>$2x^2+5x-12=0$</li></ol>\n</div>\n</div>"},{"problem_id":"unit06-0029","original_source":"cpm-10-60","source_lesson":"10.2.4","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"2","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 2: Completing the Square","source_type":"Lesson","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Perfect-square-form equations and solution-count patterns.","question_html":"<section class=\"problem\" id=\"10-60\">\n<h2>10-60</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Lesson</span> Sorted to Unit 6, Section 2: Solving Quadratics with Graphs and Square Roots</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Solves quadratic equations in perfect square form and compares cases with zero, one, or two real solutions.</div>\n<p><strong>The Number of Solutions</strong></p>\n<p>From problems in prior chapters, you know that some quadratic equations have no solutions, some have only one solution, and some have two solutions. How can you quickly determine how many solutions a quadratic equation has?</p>\n<p>The quadratic equations below are written in perfect square form. See the Math Notes box at the end of this lesson.</p>\n<p>With your team, solve the equations below and note how many solutions there are. Express your answers in both exact form and approximate decimal form. Look for patterns among those with no solution and those with only one solution. Be ready to report your patterns to the class.</p>\n<div class=\"three-col\"><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" type=\"a\"><li>$(x+4)^2=20$</li></ol></div><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"2\" type=\"a\"><li>$(7x-5)^2=-2$</li></ol></div><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"3\" type=\"a\"><li>$(2x-3)^2=49$</li></ol></div></div>\n<div class=\"three-col\"><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"4\" type=\"a\"><li>$(5-10x)^2=0$</li></ol></div><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"5\" type=\"a\"><li>$(x+2)^2=-10$</li></ol></div><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"6\" type=\"a\"><li>$(x+11)^2+5=5$</li></ol></div></div>\n</section>"},{"problem_id":"unit06-0030","original_source":"cpm-10-61","source_lesson":"10.2.4","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"2","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 2: Completing the Square","source_type":"Lesson","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Determines number of solutions from perfect-square structure.","question_html":"<section class=\"problem\" id=\"10-61\">\n<h2>10-61</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Lesson</span> Sorted to Unit 6, Section 2: Solving Quadratics with Graphs and Square Roots</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Uses perfect-square structure to determine the number of real solutions without solving.</div>\n<p>Use the patterns you found in problem 10-60 to determine quickly how many solutions there are for each quadratic equation below. You do not need to solve the equations.</p>\n<div class=\"three-col\"><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" type=\"a\"><li>$(5m-2)^2+6=0$</li></ol></div><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"2\" type=\"a\"><li>$(4+2n)^2=0$</li></ol></div><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"3\" type=\"a\"><li>$11=(7+2x)^2$</li></ol></div></div>\n</section>"},{"problem_id":"unit06-0031","original_source":"cpm-10-64","source_lesson":"10.2.4","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"2","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 2: Completing the Square","source_type":"Lesson","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Graph/table check of solution only.","question_html":"<section class=\"problem\" id=\"10-64\">\n<h2>10-64</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Lesson</span> Sorted to Unit 6, Section 2: Solving Quadratics with Graphs and Square Roots</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Uses graph/table technology to check a quadratic solution from the previous problem.</div>\n<p>Use the graph and table on your graphing calculator to check your solution to part (a) of problem 10-63.</p>\n</section>"},{"problem_id":"unit06-0032","original_source":"cpm-10-78","source_lesson":"10.2.5","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"2","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 2: Completing the Square","source_type":"Lesson","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Perfect-square equation extended to imaginary solutions.","question_html":"<section class=\"problem\" id=\"10-78\">\n<h2>10-78</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Lesson</span> Sorted to Unit 6, Section 2: Solving Quadratics with Graphs and Square Roots</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Revisits a perfect-square equation with no real solutions and extends the solution set using imaginary numbers.</div>\n<p>Consider the equation $(7x-5)^2=-2$. You previously saw this equation in part (b) of problem 10-60. What real number solutions did $(7x-5)^2=-2$ have? What solutions using imaginary numbers does the equation have?</p>\n</section>"},{"problem_id":"unit06-0033","original_source":"cpm-10-81","source_lesson":"10.2.5","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"2","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 2: Completing the Square","source_type":"Review/Preview","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Solves by square roots, including imaginary solutions.","question_html":"<section class=\"problem\" id=\"10-81\">\n<h2>10-81</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Review/Preview</span> Sorted to Unit 6, Section 2: Solving Quadratics with Graphs and Square Roots</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Solves quadratic equations by square roots, including cases that produce imaginary solutions.</div>\n<p>Use square roots to find both solutions to each equation.</p>\n<div class=\"four-col\"><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" type=\"a\"><li>$x^2-81=0$</li></ol></div><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"2\" type=\"a\"><li>$x^2-37=0$</li></ol></div><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"3\" type=\"a\"><li>$x^2+49=0$</li></ol></div><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"4\" type=\"a\"><li>$2x^2+10=0$</li></ol></div></div>\n</section>"},{"problem_id":"unit06-0034","original_source":"cpm-10-91","source_lesson":"10.2.6","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"2","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 2: Completing the Square","source_type":"Review/Preview","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Vertex-form/perfect-square reasoning about roots.","question_html":"<section class=\"problem\" id=\"10-91\">\n<h2>10-91</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Review/Preview</span> Sorted to Unit 6, Section 2: Solving Quadratics with Graphs and Square Roots</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Uses vertex form to reason about x-intercepts and then solves for real or imaginary roots.</div>\n<p>Jessie looked at the rule $y=(x-11)^2+4$ and stated, \u201cThe graph of this rule has no $x$-intercepts!\u201d</p>\n<ol class=\"lower-alpha\" type=\"a\">\n<li>How could she know without graphing?</li>\n<li>Find the roots, real or imaginary.</li>\n</ol>\n</section>"},{"problem_id":"unit06-0035","original_source":"cpm-10-125","source_lesson":"10.3.2","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"2","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 2: Completing the Square","source_type":"Review/Preview","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Completes the square to find vertex and maximum.","question_html":"<section class=\"problem\" id=\"10-125\">\n<h2>10-125</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Review/Preview</span> Sorted to Unit 6, Section 4: Completing the Square</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Completes the square for a downward-opening quadratic to locate the vertex and maximum value.</div>\n<p>Joaquin needed to find the maximum value of $y=-x^2+4x-1$ but was stuck.</p>\n<p>\u201cNo problem,\u201d said Thao. \u201cThe parabola opens downward so just complete the square to find the vertex. The $y$-value of the vertex will be the maximum.\u201d</p>\n<p>\u201cI know that,\u201d said Joaquin. \u201cThe problem is that it is $-x^2$.\u201d</p>\n<p>\u201cWhat if we multiply everything by $-1$? Can we now complete the square?\u201d</p>\n<ol class=\"lower-alpha\" type=\"a\"><li>Multiply the equation by $-1$ so you have $-y=$ ...</li><li>Complete the square on the right side.</li><li>Multiply the equation by $-1$ so you are back to $y=$ ...</li><li>Identify the vertex and the maximum value.</li></ol>\n</section>"},{"problem_id":"unit06-0036","original_source":"cpm-11-21","source_lesson":"11.1.2","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"2","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 2: Completing the Square","source_type":"Review/Preview","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Solves equations and inequalities by completing the square; prescribed method dominates.","question_html":"<section class=\"problem\" id=\"11-21\">\n<h2>11-21</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Review/Preview</span> Sorted to Unit 6, Section 4: Completing the Square</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Solves equations and inequalities by completing the square, including interval reasoning for quadratic inequalities.</div>\n<p>Solve the equations and inequalities below by completing the square.</p>\n<div class=\"four-col\"><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" type=\"a\"><li>$x^2-2x-3\\le 0$</li></ol></div><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"2\" type=\"a\"><li>$x^2+4x=3$</li></ol></div><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"3\" type=\"a\"><li>$x^2+12x+39&gt;0$</li></ol></div><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"4\" type=\"a\"><li>$x^2-3x-13.75=0$</li></ol></div></div>\n</section>"},{"problem_id":"unit06-0037","original_source":"cpm-11-89","source_lesson":"11.3.2","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"2","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 2: Completing the Square","source_type":"Review/Preview","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Converts a quadratic from standard form to graphing form by completing the square.","question_html":"<section class=\"problem\" id=\"11-89\"><h2>11-89</h2><div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Review/Preview</span> Sorted to Unit 6, Section 4: Completing the Square</div><div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Completes the square to rewrite a quadratic from standard form into graphing form.</div><p>Complete the square to convert $y=\\frac{1}{2}x^2-2x+5$ into graphing form.</p></section>"},{"problem_id":"unit06-0038","original_source":"cpm-11-100","source_lesson":"11.3.3","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"2","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 2: Completing the Square","source_type":"Review/Preview","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Solves quadratics by completing the square in exact form.","question_html":"<section class=\"problem\" id=\"11-100\">\n<h2>11-100</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Review/Preview</span> Sorted to Unit 6, Section 4: Completing the Square</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Solves quadratic equations by completing the square and leaves answers in exact form.</div>\n<p>Solve the quadratics below by completing the square. Leave your solutions in exact form.</p>\n<div class=\"two-col\"><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" type=\"a\"><li>$x^2-6x-12=0$</li></ol></div><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"2\" type=\"a\"><li>$x^2-3=4x$</li></ol></div></div>\n</section>"},{"problem_id":"unit06-0039","original_source":"cpm-8-96","source_lesson":"8.2.4","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"3","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 3: Quadratic Formula","source_type":"Review/Preview","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Evaluates expressions matching quadratic-formula structure and compares to factoring solutions.","question_html":"<section class=\"problem\" id=\"8-96\">\n<h2>8-96</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Review/Preview</span> Sorted to Unit 6, Section 3: Quadratic Formula</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Evaluates expressions that match the quadratic formula structure and compares results to factored solutions.</div>\n<div><p>Calculate the expressions below. Then compare your answers from parts (a) and (b) to those in part (a) of problem 8-95, and parts (c) and (d) to part (b) in problem 8-95. What do you notice?</p>\n<div class=\"two-col\"><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" type=\"a\"><li><p>$\\frac{-6+\\sqrt{6^2-4(1)(-40)}}{2\\cdot1}$</p></li></ol></div><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"2\" type=\"a\"><li><p>$\\frac{-6-\\sqrt{6^2-(4)(1)(-40)}}{2\\cdot1}$</p></li></ol></div></div>\n<div class=\"two-col\"><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"3\" type=\"a\"><li><p>$\\frac{-13-\\sqrt{13^2-(4)(2)(-24)}}{2\\cdot2}$</p></li></ol></div><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"4\" type=\"a\"><li><p>$\\frac{-13+\\sqrt{13^2-(4)(2)(-24)}}{2\\cdot2}$</p></li></ol></div></div></div>\n</section>"},{"problem_id":"unit06-0040","original_source":"cpm-9-13","source_lesson":"9.1.2","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"3","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 3: Solving Quadratics with the Quadratic Formula","source_type":"Lesson","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Introduces the Quadratic Formula, identifies a, b, and c, and solves exactly and approximately.","question_html":"<section class=\"problem\" id=\"9-13\">\n<h2>9-13</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Lesson</span> Sorted to Unit 6, Section 3: Quadratic Formula</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Introduces the Quadratic Formula, identifies a, b, and c in standard form, and solves a non-factorable quadratic exactly and approximately.</div>\n<div><p><strong>QUADRATIC FORMULA</strong></p>\n<p>One way to calculate the roots of a parabola is by using the Quadratic Formula, shown below. This formula uses values $a$, $b$, and $c$ from a quadratic equation written in standard form.</p>\n<p class=\"center display-math\">$$x=\\frac{-b\\pm\\sqrt{b^2-4ac}}{2a}$$</p>\n<ol class=\"lower-alpha\" type=\"a\">\n<li><p>When the quadratic equation is written in <strong>standard form</strong>, that is, it looks like $ax^2+bx+c=0$, then $a$ is the number of $x^2$-terms, $b$ is the number of $x$-terms, and $c$ is the constant. If $x^2-3x-7=0$, then what are $a$, $b$, and $c$?</p></li>\n<li><p>The Quadratic Formula calculates <em>two</em> possible answers by using the \u201c$\\pm$\u201d symbol. This symbol, read as \u201cplus or minus,\u201d is shorthand notation that tells you to calculate the formula twice: once with addition and once with subtraction in the numerator. Therefore, every Quadratic Formula problem is really two different problems unless the value of $\\sqrt{b^2-4ac}$ is $0$.</p>\n<p class=\"center\">$\\pm$</p>\n<p class=\"center\">$\\swarrow \\qquad\\qquad \\searrow$</p>\n<p class=\"center\">$x=\\frac{-b+\\sqrt{b^2-4ac}}{2a}\\ \\text{ or }\\ x=\\frac{-b-\\sqrt{b^2-4ac}}{2a}$</p>\n<p>Carefully substitute $a$, $b$, and $c$ from $x^2-3x-7=0$ into the Quadratic Formula. Simplify each expression, once using addition and once using subtraction, to solve for $x$. Write your solution for $x$ in both exact form and approximate form.</p></li>\n<li><p>Make a graph with your graphing calculator to verify your solution.</p></li>\n</ol></div>\n</section>"},{"problem_id":"unit06-0041","original_source":"cpm-9-15","source_lesson":"9.1.2","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"3","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 3: Solving Quadratics with the Quadratic Formula","source_type":"Lesson","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Uses the Quadratic Formula, including no-real-solution cases.","question_html":"<section class=\"problem\" id=\"9-15\">\n<h2>9-15</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Lesson</span> Sorted to Unit 6, Section 3: Quadratic Formula</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Uses the Quadratic Formula to solve quadratic equations, including equations with no real solutions.</div>\n<div><p>Use the Quadratic Formula to solve the equations below for $x$, if possible. Check your solutions with your graphing calculator.</p>\n<div class=\"two-col\">\n<div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" type=\"a\"><li><p>$3x^2+7x+2=0$</p></li></ol></div>\n<div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"2\" type=\"a\"><li><p>$2x^2-9x-35=0$</p></li></ol></div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"two-col\">\n<div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"3\" type=\"a\"><li><p>$8x^2+10x+3=0$</p></li></ol></div>\n<div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"4\" type=\"a\"><li><p>$x^2-5x+9=0$</p></li></ol></div>\n</div></div>\n</section>"},{"problem_id":"unit06-0042","original_source":"cpm-9-16","source_lesson":"9.1.2","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"3","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 3: Solving Quadratics with the Quadratic Formula","source_type":"Learning Log","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Learning-log explanation of how to use the Quadratic Formula.","question_html":"<section class=\"problem\" id=\"9-16\">\n<h2>9-16</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Lesson</span> Sorted to Unit 6, Section 3: Quadratic Formula</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Learning-log reflection explaining how to use the Quadratic Formula with an example.</div>\n<div><p>In your Learning Log, describe how to use the Quadratic Formula. Be sure to include an example. Title this entry \u201cQuadratic Formula\u201d and include today\u2019s date.</p></div>\n</section>"},{"problem_id":"unit06-0043","original_source":"cpm-9-18","source_lesson":"9.1.2","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"3","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 3: Solving Quadratics with the Quadratic Formula","source_type":"Review/Preview","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Uses the Quadratic Formula on a factorable quadratic and compares to factoring.","question_html":"<section class=\"problem\" id=\"9-18\">\n<h2>9-18</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Review/Preview</span> Sorted to Unit 6, Section 3: Quadratic Formula</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Uses the Quadratic Formula on a factorable quadratic and compares the result to a factoring solution.</div>\n<div><p>Use the Quadratic Formula to solve $x^2-13x+42=0$. Did your solution match the solution from part (a) of problem 9-17?</p></div>\n</section>"},{"problem_id":"unit06-0044","original_source":"cpm-9-24","source_lesson":"9.1.3","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"3","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 3: Solving Quadratics with the Quadratic Formula","source_type":"Lesson","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Solves the same quadratic by factoring and by the Quadratic Formula; formula use dominates.","question_html":"<section class=\"problem\" id=\"9-24\">\n<h2>9-24</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Lesson</span> Sorted to Unit 6, Section 3: Quadratic Formula</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Solves the same quadratic by factoring and by the Quadratic Formula and compares the solutions.</div>\n<div><p>For the quadratic equation $6x^2+11x-10=0$:</p>\n<ol class=\"lower-alpha\" type=\"a\">\n<li><p>Solve it using the Zero Product Property.</p></li>\n<li><p>Solve it using the Quadratic Formula.</p></li>\n<li><p>Did the solutions from parts (a) and (b) match? If not, why not?</p></li>\n</ol></div>\n</section>"},{"problem_id":"unit06-0045","original_source":"cpm-9-25","source_lesson":"9.1.3","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"3","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 3: Solving Quadratics with the Quadratic Formula","source_type":"Lesson","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Applies the Quadratic Formula to equations not already in standard form.","question_html":"<section class=\"problem\" id=\"9-25\">\n<h2>9-25</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Lesson</span> Sorted to Unit 6, Section 3: Quadratic Formula</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Solves quadratic equations that may not already be in standard form, including missing-term and rearranged equations.</div>\n<div><p>As the Math Notes box from Lesson 9.1.2 demonstrated, the Quadratic Formula can solve any quadratic equation $ax^2+bx+c=0$ if $a\\ne 0$. But what if the equation is not in standard form? What if terms are missing? Consider these questions as you solve the quadratic equations below. Share your ideas with your teammates and be prepared to demonstrate your process for the class.</p>\n<div class=\"two-col\">\n<div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" type=\"a\"><li><p>$4x^2-121=0$</p></li></ol></div>\n<div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"2\" type=\"a\"><li><p>$2x^2-2-3x=0$</p></li></ol></div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"two-col\">\n<div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"3\" type=\"a\"><li><p>$15x^2-165x=-630$</p></li></ol></div>\n<div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"4\" type=\"a\"><li><p>$36x^2+25=60x$</p></li></ol></div>\n</div></div>\n</section>"},{"problem_id":"unit06-0046","original_source":"cpm-9-28","source_lesson":"9.1.3","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"3","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 3: Solving Quadratics with the Quadratic Formula","source_type":"Review/Preview","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Uses the Quadratic Formula on a previously factorable equation and compares methods.","question_html":"<section class=\"problem\" id=\"9-28\">\n<h2>9-28</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Review/Preview</span> Sorted to Unit 6, Section 3: Quadratic Formula</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Uses the Quadratic Formula to solve a previously factorable quadratic and compares methods.</div>\n<div><p>Use the Quadratic Formula to solve part (b) of problem 9-27 above. Did your solution match the solution you got by factoring and using the Zero Product Property in part (b) of problem 9-27?</p></div>\n</section>"},{"problem_id":"unit06-0047","original_source":"cpm-9-52","source_lesson":"9.2.1","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"3","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 3: Solving Quadratics with the Quadratic Formula","source_type":"Review/Preview","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Mixed quadratic-solving review including non-factorable cases.","question_html":"<section class=\"problem\" id=\"9-52\">\n<h2>9-52</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Review/Preview</span> Sorted to Unit 6, Section 3: Quadratic Formula</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Solves quadratic equations using appropriate algebraic methods, including non-factorable cases.</div>\n<div><p>Solve the following quadratic equations. Check your solutions, if possible.</p>\n<div class=\"two-col\">\n<div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" type=\"a\"><li><p>$2k^2+k-6=0$</p></li></ol></div>\n<div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"2\" type=\"a\"><li><p>$m^2=9$</p></li></ol></div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"two-col\">\n<div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"3\" type=\"a\"><li><p>$w(2w+8)=24$</p></li></ol></div>\n<div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"4\" type=\"a\"><li><p>$3n^2-4n=5$</p></li></ol></div>\n</div></div>\n</section>"},{"problem_id":"unit06-0048","original_source":"cpm-9-64","source_lesson":"9.2.2","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"3","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 3: Solving Quadratics with the Quadratic Formula","source_type":"Review/Preview","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Quadratic-solving review.","question_html":"<section class=\"problem\" id=\"9-64\">\n<h2>9-64</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Review/Preview</span> Sorted to Unit 5, Section 2: Factoring Quadratic Expressions</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Factors quadratic expressions completely, including GCF and non-factorable recognition.</div>\n<div>\n<p>Factor the expressions below completely, if possible.</p>\n<div class=\"two-col\">\n<div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" type=\"a\"><li><p>$4x^2-20x+25$</p></li></ol></div>\n<div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"2\" type=\"a\"><li><p>$x^2+11x-2$</p></li></ol></div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"two-col\">\n<div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"3\" type=\"a\"><li><p>$3x^2-12x$</p></li></ol></div>\n<div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"4\" type=\"a\"><li><p>$10x^2-35x-20$</p></li></ol></div>\n</div></div>\n</section>"},{"problem_id":"unit06-0049","original_source":"cpm-9-99","source_lesson":"9.4.1","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"3","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 3: Solving Quadratics with the Quadratic Formula","source_type":"Review/Preview","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Quadratic-solving review.","question_html":"<section class=\"problem\" id=\"9-99\">\n<h2>9-99</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Review/Preview</span> Sorted to Unit 6, Section 4: Completing the Square</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Solves a quadratic equation by completing the square and gives exact radical solutions.</div>\n<div><p>Solve the equation below by completing the square. Give your answer in exact radical form.</p><p class=\"center\">$x^2-6x+3=0$</p></div>\n</section>"},{"problem_id":"unit06-0050","original_source":"cpm-CL9-125a","source_lesson":"Chapter 9 Closure","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"3","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 3: Solving Quadratics with the Quadratic Formula","source_type":"Closure","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Explicitly solved by Quadratic Formula.","question_html":"<div class=\"card\" id=\"CL9125\">\n<div class=\"problem-title\">CL 9-125</div>\n<p>Solve each quadratic equation using the specified method.</p>\n<div class=\"grid-2\">\n<ol type=\"a\"><li><span class=\"method\">The Quadratic Formula</span><br/>$0=3x^2+4x-7$</li></ol>\n<ol start=\"2\" type=\"a\"><li><span class=\"method\">Factoring</span><br/>$x^2-3x-18=0$</li></ol>\n<ol start=\"3\" type=\"a\"><li><span class=\"method\">Completing the square</span><br/>$x^2+4x+1=0$</li></ol>\n<ol start=\"4\" type=\"a\"><li><span class=\"method\">Using a graph</span><br/>$2x^2+5x-12=0$</li></ol>\n</div>\n</div>"},{"problem_id":"unit06-0051","original_source":"cpm-10-62","source_lesson":"10.2.4","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"3","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 3: Quadratic Formula","source_type":"Lesson","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Standard-form solution-count/discriminant reasoning.","question_html":"<section class=\"problem\" id=\"10-62\">\n<h2>10-62</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Lesson</span> Sorted to Unit 6, Section 3: Quadratic Formula</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Investigates how the constant term in standard form affects whether a quadratic has zero, one, or two real solutions.</div>\n<p>How can you tell how many solutions an equation in standard form, $ax^2+bx+c=0$, has? Explore that question by completing this investigation:</p>\n<ol class=\"lower-alpha\" type=\"a\">\n<li>Solve the quadratic equation $2x^2-3x+\\frac{1}{2}=0$. Write the solution in both exact form and approximate decimal form.</li>\n<li>Change the $\\frac{1}{2}$ at the end of the equation to another number so that you have an equation with no real solutions. What would the $\\frac{1}{2}$ have to be so there is only one solution?</li>\n<li>Explain how you can tell from the standard form, $ax^2+bx+c=0$, whether the equation will have zero, one, or two real solutions.</li>\n</ol>\n</section>"},{"problem_id":"unit06-0052","original_source":"cpm-10-63","source_lesson":"10.2.4","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"3","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 3: Quadratic Formula","source_type":"Lesson","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Connects quadratic functions to number and type of roots/intercepts.","question_html":"<section class=\"problem\" id=\"10-63\">\n<h2>10-63</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Lesson</span> Sorted to Unit 6, Section 3: Quadratic Formula</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Connects quadratic functions to the number and form of solutions/intercepts.</div>\n<p>How many solutions do the equations below have? How can you express the solutions?</p>\n<div class=\"two-col\"><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" type=\"a\"><li>$9x^2+4x-6=y$</li></ol></div><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"2\" type=\"a\"><li>$\\left(\\frac{3}{8}x+1\\right)^2=y$</li></ol></div></div>\n</section>"},{"problem_id":"unit06-0053","original_source":"cpm-10-66","source_lesson":"10.2.4","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"3","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 3: Quadratic Formula","source_type":"Learning Log","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Summarizes number of solutions across quadratic forms.","question_html":"<section class=\"problem\" id=\"10-66\">\n<h2>10-66</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Lesson</span> Sorted to Other: Reflection / Study Skills</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Learning Log prompt asks students to summarize how to determine the number of solutions for quadratic equations in multiple forms.</div>\n<p><strong>Learning Log</strong></p>\n<p>How can you tell, without solving, how many solutions a quadratic equation has? Be sure to consider all three forms of a quadratic equation in the Math Notes box below. Respond in a Learning Log entry. Be sure to include examples for each. Title this entry \u201cNumber of Solutions\u201d and include today\u2019s date.</p>\n</section>"},{"problem_id":"unit06-0054","original_source":"cpm-10-74","source_lesson":"10.2.5","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"3","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 3: Quadratic Formula","source_type":"Lesson","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Derives the Quadratic Formula by completing the square.","question_html":"<section class=\"problem\" id=\"10-74\">\n<h2>10-74</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Lesson</span> Sorted to Unit 6, Section 3: Quadratic Formula</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Derives the Quadratic Formula from standard form by completing the square and interpreting each algebraic step.</div>\n<p><strong>Derivation of the Quadratic Formula</strong></p>\n<p>In Chapter 9 you learned how to solve quadratic equations with the Quadratic Formula. In the Math Notes box in Lesson 9.1.2, you saw one way to derive the Quadratic Formula.</p>\n<p>Today you will derive the Quadratic Formula in a different way\u2014by completing the square. You will also verify that the Quadratic Formula provides the solution for <em>any</em> quadratic equation. You will start with the equation in standard form, $ax^2+bx+c=0$, complete the square, and solve for $x$ to prove that:</p>\n<p class=\"center\">$$x=\\frac{-b\\pm\\sqrt{b^2-4ac}}{2a}$$</p>\n<p>Fold a piece of lined paper in half vertically, make a crease, and then unfold the paper. Copy the algebraic steps shown below onto the left-hand side of your paper. On the right-hand side, for each of the ten steps, write what was done to get the equation in that step.</p>\n<p>Problem: Solve the equation $ax^2+bx+c=0$.</p>\n<ol>\n<li>$ax^2+bx=-c$</li>\n<li>$x^2+\\frac{b}{a}x=-\\frac{c}{a}$</li>\n<li>Draw a generic rectangle like the one below to complete the square. What expression should go in the bolded squares? What are the dimensions of the rectangle? What expression goes in the upper-right corner?\n  <div class=\"visual-row\"><div><div class=\"generic-rect\"><div>$x^2$</div><div class=\"bold\"></div><div class=\"bold\"></div><div></div></div><p class=\"center muted\">Generic rectangle for completing the square</p></div></div>\n</li>\n<li>$\\left(x+\\frac{b}{2a}\\right)^2-\\frac{b^2}{4a^2}=-\\frac{c}{a}$</li>\n<li>$\\left(x+\\frac{b}{2a}\\right)^2=-\\frac{c}{a}+\\frac{b^2}{4a^2}$</li>\n<li>$\\left(x+\\frac{b}{2a}\\right)^2=\\frac{b^2}{4a^2}-\\frac{c}{a}$</li>\n<li>$\\left(x+\\frac{b}{2a}\\right)^2=\\frac{b^2-4ac}{4a^2}$<br/><br/>You\u2019re very close! Now solve for $x$.</li>\n<li>$\\left|x+\\frac{b}{2a}\\right|=\\frac{\\sqrt{b^2-4ac}}{2a}$</li>\n<li>$x+\\frac{b}{2a}=\\pm\\frac{\\sqrt{b^2-4ac}}{2a}$</li>\n<li>$-\\frac{b}{2a}\\pm\\frac{\\sqrt{b^2-4ac}}{2a}$<br/><br/>Finally, simplify the result.</li>\n<li>$x=\\frac{-b\\pm\\sqrt{b^2-4ac}}{2a}$</li>\n</ol>\n<p class=\"indent-1\">Since any quadratic polynomial can be written as $ax^2+bx+c=0$, this is the solution to any quadratic polynomial.</p>\n</section>"},{"problem_id":"unit06-0055","original_source":"cpm-10-75","source_lesson":"10.2.5","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"3","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 3: Quadratic Formula","source_type":"Lesson","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Uses formula/discriminant reasoning to determine number of intercepts.","question_html":"<section class=\"problem\" id=\"10-75\">\n<h2>10-75</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Lesson</span> Sorted to Unit 6, Section 3: Quadratic Formula</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Uses the Quadratic Formula/discriminant to determine the number of intercepts of quadratic functions.</div>\n<p>Use the Quadratic Formula to determine how many intercepts each of the following quadratic functions have. You do not actually have to find the intercepts. Check your answer by graphing the parabola on your calculator.</p>\n<div class=\"two-col\"><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" type=\"a\"><li>$8x^2+14x-15=y$</li></ol></div><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"2\" type=\"a\"><li>$8x+0.5x^2=y-3$</li></ol></div></div>\n<div class=\"two-col\"><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"3\" type=\"a\"><li>$x^2-10x+30=y$</li></ol></div><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"4\" type=\"a\"><li>$4x^2-4x+1=y$</li></ol></div></div>\n</section>"},{"problem_id":"unit06-0056","original_source":"cpm-10-77","source_lesson":"10.2.5","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"3","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 3: Quadratic Formula","source_type":"Lesson","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Applies Quadratic Formula to non-real solutions.","question_html":"<section class=\"problem\" id=\"10-77\">\n<h2>10-77</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Lesson</span> Sorted to Unit 6, Section 3: Quadratic Formula</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Applies the Quadratic Formula to a quadratic with non-real solutions and connects the result to imaginary numbers.</div>\n<p>Consider the equation $x^2-10x+30=y$ from part (c) of problem 10-75. Use the Quadratic Formula to solve for $y=0$. Read the Math Notes box in this lesson to see how imaginary numbers fall into the overall organization of the number system.</p>\n</section>"},{"problem_id":"unit06-0057","original_source":"cpm-10-139","source_lesson":"10.3.3","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"3","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 3: Quadratic Formula","source_type":"Review/Preview","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Determines number of x-intercepts through root/discriminant reasoning.","question_html":"<section class=\"problem\" id=\"10-139\">\n<h2>10-139</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Review/Preview</span> Sorted to Unit 6, Section 2: Solving Quadratics with Graphs and Square Roots</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Determines number of x-intercepts without graphing by analyzing quadratic roots/discriminants.</div>\n<p>Without graphing, determine if the graph of each rule below has zero, one, or two $x$-intercepts. Show all work.</p>\n<div class=\"two-col\"><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" type=\"a\"><li>$y=6x^2+7x-20$</li></ol></div><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"2\" type=\"a\"><li>$y=x^2-8x+16$</li></ol></div><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"3\" type=\"a\"><li>$y=2x^2+x+3$</li></ol></div><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"4\" type=\"a\"><li>$y=(2x+1)^2$</li></ol></div></div>\n</section>"},{"problem_id":"unit06-0058","original_source":"cpm-CL10-151b","source_lesson":"Chapter 10 Closure","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"3","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 3: Quadratic Formula","source_type":"Closure","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Explains why no real solutions exist; root/discriminant reasoning.","question_html":"<div class=\"card\" id=\"CL10151\">\n<div class=\"problem-title\">CL 10-151</div>\n<p>For the quadratic function $f(x)=(x-3)^2+4$:</p>\n<ol type=\"a\">\n<li>Identify the vertex and tell if it is the maximum or minimum point of the function.</li>\n<li>Why does $(x-3)^2+4=0$ have no real solutions?</li>\n<li>Find the imaginary roots of the function.</li>\n</ol>\n</div>"},{"problem_id":"unit06-0059","original_source":"cpm-11-11","source_lesson":"11.1.1","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"3","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 3: Quadratic Formula","source_type":"Review/Preview","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Solves quadratics and explains when solutions are not real.","question_html":"<section class=\"problem\" id=\"11-11\">\n<h2>11-11</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Review/Preview</span> Sorted to Unit 6, Section 3: Quadratic Formula</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Solves quadratic equations and explains when solutions are not real.</div>\n<p>Solve each quadratic equation. If the solution is not a real number, explain why.</p><div class=\"two-col\"><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" type=\"a\"><li>$9x^2-6x+1=0$</li></ol></div><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"2\" type=\"a\"><li>$x^2+x+1=0$</li></ol></div></div>\n</section>"},{"problem_id":"unit06-0060","original_source":"cpm-11-23","source_lesson":"11.1.2","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"3","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 3: Quadratic Formula","source_type":"Review/Preview","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Determines number of solutions using structure, factoring, and repeated-root reasoning.","question_html":"<section class=\"problem\" id=\"11-23\">\n<h2>11-23</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Review/Preview</span> Sorted to Unit 6, Section 3: Quadratic Formula</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Determines the number of solutions for linear and quadratic equations using structure, factoring, and repeated roots.</div>\n<p>How many solutions does each equation below have?</p>\n<div class=\"four-col\"><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" type=\"a\"><li>$4x+3=3x+3$</li></ol></div><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"2\" type=\"a\"><li>$3(x-4)-x=5+2x$</li></ol></div><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"3\" type=\"a\"><li>$(5x-2)(x+4)=0$</li></ol></div><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"4\" type=\"a\"><li>$x^2-4x+4=0$</li></ol></div></div>\n</section>"},{"problem_id":"unit06-0061","original_source":"cpm-11-33","source_lesson":"11.2.1","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"3","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 3: Quadratic Formula","source_type":"Review/Preview","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Solves quadratics and determines when no real solution exists; root/discriminant reasoning dominates.","question_html":"<section class=\"problem\" id=\"11-33\">\n<h2>11-33</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Review/Preview</span> Sorted to Unit 6, Section 3: Quadratic Formula</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Finds real solutions to quadratic equations and recognizes when an equation has no real solution.</div>\n<p>Find the real solutions to the equations below using any method of your choice.</p>\n<ol class=\"lower-alpha\" type=\"a\"><li>$2x^2=2-3x$</li><li>$(2x-3)^2+4=0$</li></ol>\n</section>"},{"problem_id":"unit06-0062","original_source":"cpm-11-101","source_lesson":"11.3.3","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"3","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 3: Quadratic Formula","source_type":"Review/Preview","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Determines number of real solutions using perfect-square and discriminant reasoning.","question_html":"<section class=\"problem\" id=\"11-101\">\n<h2>11-101</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Review/Preview</span> Sorted to Unit 6, Section 3: Quadratic Formula</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Determines the number of real solutions of quadratic equations without fully solving, including perfect-square and discriminant reasoning.</div>\n<p>Determine the number of solutions for each of the quadratics below. Note: You do not need to solve the quadratics.</p>\n<div class=\"two-col\"><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" type=\"a\"><li>$(x-5)^2=-6$</li></ol></div><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"2\" type=\"a\"><li>$312x^2+514x+181=0$</li></ol></div></div>\n<div class=\"two-col\"><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"3\" type=\"a\"><li>$(x+3)^2-10=0$</li></ol></div><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"4\" type=\"a\"><li>$4x^2+49=28x$</li></ol></div></div>\n</section>"},{"problem_id":"unit06-0063","original_source":"cpm-11-118","source_lesson":"11.3.4","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"3","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 3: Quadratic Formula","source_type":"Review/Preview","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Determines the number of real solutions without solving.","question_html":"<section class=\"problem\" id=\"11-118\">\n<h2>11-118</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Review/Preview</span> Sorted to Unit 6, Section 3: Quadratic Formula</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Determines the number of real solutions to quadratic equations without solving, using square/root and discriminant reasoning.</div>\n<p>Determine the number of solutions for each of the quadratics below. Note: You do not need to solve the quadratics.</p><div class=\"two-col\"><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" type=\"a\"><li>$(x-2)^2=-3$</li></ol></div><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"2\" type=\"a\"><li>$6x^2-x-2=0$</li></ol></div></div><div class=\"two-col\"><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"3\" type=\"a\"><li>$4x^2-4x+1=0$</li></ol></div><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"4\" type=\"a\"><li>$427x^2+731x-280=0$</li></ol></div></div>\n</section>"},{"problem_id":"unit06-0064","original_source":"cpm-8-98","source_lesson":"8.2.5","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"4","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 4: Completing the Square","source_type":"Lesson","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Motivates completing the square when factoring/simple intercept methods do not efficiently reveal vertex information.","question_html":"<section class=\"problem\" id=\"8-98\">\n<h2>8-98</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Lesson</span> Sorted to Unit 6, Section 4: Completing the Square</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Introduces the need for completing the square when factoring or simple intercept methods do not easily give exact vertex information.</div>\n<p>Use the Zero Product Property to find the exact vertex of $y=x^2+8x+10$. What went wrong? How could you work around this problem?</p>\n</section>"},{"problem_id":"unit06-0065","original_source":"cpm-8-99","source_lesson":"8.2.5","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"4","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 4: Completing the Square","source_type":"Lesson","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Uses graphing form to find exact x-intercepts and vertex after completing the square.","question_html":"<section class=\"problem\" id=\"8-99\">\n<h2>8-99</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Lesson</span> Sorted to Unit 6, Section 4: Completing the Square</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Uses graphing form to find exact x-intercepts and vertex after completing the square.</div>\n<p>The function from problem 8-98 can be rewritten in graphing form as $y=(x+4)^2-6$. Find the exact <em>$x$</em>-intercepts and vertex. Make a sketch, then check your sketch with your graphing calculator.</p>\n</section>"},{"problem_id":"unit06-0066","original_source":"cpm-8-100","source_lesson":"8.2.5","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"4","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 4: Completing the Square","source_type":"Lesson","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Uses algebra tiles to explain completing the square and convert standard form to graphing form.","question_html":"<section class=\"problem\" id=\"8-100\">\n<h2>8-100</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Lesson</span> Sorted to Unit 6, Section 4: Completing the Square</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Uses algebra tiles to explain completing the square and convert standard form to graphing form.</div>\n<p><strong>COMPLETING THE SQUARE</strong></p>\n<p>Jessica was at home struggling with her Algebra homework. She had missed class and did not understand the new method called completing the square. She was supposed to use it to change <em>$y=x^2+8x+10$</em> to graphing form. Then her younger sister, who was playing with algebra tiles, said that the tiles could help. Explore using the <a class=\"etool-link\" href=\"https://technology.cpm.org/general/tiles/\" rel=\"noopener\" target=\"_blank\">8-100 Student eTool</a>.</p>\n<p>Anita explained: \u201c<em>$x^2+8x+10$ would look like this</em>.\u201d</p>\n<img alt=\"Algebra tiles showing one x-squared tile, eight x-tiles, and ten unit tiles.\" class=\"wide-img\" src=\"assets/8-100a.png\"/>\n<div class=\"two-col\"><div>\n<p>Jessica arranged her tiles on an equation mat and realized she needed $16$ small unit tiles to fill in the corner, but she only had $10$.</p>\n<p>She drew the outline of the whole square and said that to <strong>complete the square</strong>, she needed to add six tiles to each side of the equation.</p>\n</div><div><img alt=\"Equation mat showing the missing tiles needed to complete the square.\" class=\"medium-img\" src=\"assets/8-100b.png\"/></div></div>\n<img alt=\"Equation mat after adding six unit tiles to each side to complete the square.\" class=\"wide-img\" src=\"assets/8-100c.png\"/>\n<p>Now the equation can be rewritten as $y+6=(x+4)^2$, so the graphing form is $y=(x+4)^2-6$.</p>\n<p>How can you use your graphing calculator to verify that <em>$y=x^2+8x+10$</em> and <em>$y=(x+4)^2-6$</em> are equivalent functions?</p>\n</section>","resources":[{"label":"8-100 Student eTool","href":"https://technology.cpm.org/general/tiles/"}]},{"problem_id":"unit06-0067","original_source":"cpm-8-101","source_lesson":"8.2.5","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"4","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 4: Completing the Square","source_type":"Lesson","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Writes quadratic functions in graphing form and identifies vertex and y-intercept.","question_html":"<section class=\"problem\" id=\"8-101\">\n<h2>8-101</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Lesson</span> Sorted to Unit 6, Section 4: Completing the Square</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Writes quadratic functions in graphing form and identifies vertex and y-intercept.</div>\n<p>Write each function in graphing form, then state the vertex and <em>$y$</em>-intercept of each parabola.</p>\n<div class=\"two-col\"><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" type=\"a\"><li><p>$f(x)=x^2+6x+7$</p></li></ol></div><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"2\" type=\"a\"><li><p>$f(x)=x^2+4x+11$</p></li></ol></div></div>\n</section>"},{"problem_id":"unit06-0068","original_source":"cpm-8-102","source_lesson":"8.2.5","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"4","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 4: Completing the Square","source_type":"Lesson","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Completes the square with extra constants and interprets vertex, intercepts, and graph.","question_html":"<section class=\"problem\" id=\"8-102\">\n<h2>8-102</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Lesson</span> Sorted to Unit 6, Section 4: Completing the Square</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Completes the square when the constant term is larger than needed and interprets vertex, intercepts, and graph.</div>\n<p>Help Jessica with a new problem. She needs to complete the square to write <em>$y=x^2+4x+9$</em> in graphing form.</p>\n<ol class=\"lower-alpha\" type=\"a\"><li><p>Draw tiles to help her figure out how to make this expression into a square. Does she have too few or too many unit squares this time? Write her function in graphing form.</p></li><li><p>Find the vertex and the <em>$x$</em>-intercepts. What happened? What does that mean?</p></li><li><p>Algebraically find the <em>$y$</em>-intercept. Sketch the graph.</p></li></ol>\n</section>"},{"problem_id":"unit06-0069","original_source":"cpm-8-103","source_lesson":"8.2.5","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"4","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 4: Completing the Square","source_type":"Lesson","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Completes the square with an odd linear coefficient and fractional side lengths.","question_html":"<section class=\"problem\" id=\"8-103\">\n<h2>8-103</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Lesson</span> Sorted to Unit 6, Section 4: Completing the Square</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Completes the square with an odd linear coefficient by splitting x-tiles and using fractional side lengths.</div>\n<p>How could you complete the square to change <em>$f(x)=x^2+5x+2$</em> into graphing form? How would you split the five <em>$x$</em>-tiles into two equal parts?</p>\n<p>Jessica decided to use force! She cut one tile in half, as shown below. Then she added her two small unit tiles.</p>\n<img alt=\"Two algebra-tile figures labeled A and B showing a square built with x plus 2.5 side lengths and missing unit tiles.\" class=\"wide-img\" src=\"assets/8-103.png\"/>\n<ol class=\"lower-alpha\" type=\"a\"><li><p>How many small unit tiles are missing from Jessica\u2019s square?</p></li><li><p>Write the graphing form of the function, name the vertex, and sketch the graph.</p></li></ol>\n</section>"},{"problem_id":"unit06-0070","original_source":"cpm-8-104","source_lesson":"8.2.5","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"4","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 4: Completing the Square","source_type":"Lesson","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Practices completing the square to write graphing form and identify vertex/y-intercept.","question_html":"<section class=\"problem\" id=\"8-104\">\n<h2>8-104</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Lesson</span> Sorted to Unit 6, Section 4: Completing the Square</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Practices completing the square to write graphing form and identify vertex and y-intercept.</div>\n<p>Write each function in graphing form, then state the vertex and <em>$y$</em>-intercept of each parabola.</p>\n<div class=\"two-col\"><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" type=\"a\"><li><p>$f(x)=x^2+10x$</p></li></ol></div><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"2\" type=\"a\"><li><p>$f(x)=x^2+7x+2$</p></li></ol></div></div>\n</section>"},{"problem_id":"unit06-0071","original_source":"cpm-8-105","source_lesson":"8.2.5","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"4","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 4: Completing the Square","source_type":"Lesson","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Generalizes completing the square for f(x)=x^2+bx+c.","question_html":"<section class=\"problem\" id=\"8-105\">\n<h2>8-105</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Lesson</span> Sorted to Unit 6, Section 4: Completing the Square</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Generalizes completing the square for f(x)=x^2+bx+c.</div>\n<p><strong>GENERALIZATION CHALLENGE</strong></p><p>Work with your team to write the graphing form for <em>$f(x)=x^2+bx+c$</em>. Be prepared to share your strategies with the class.</p>\n</section>"},{"problem_id":"unit06-0072","original_source":"cpm-8-106","source_lesson":"8.2.5","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"4","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 4: Completing the Square","source_type":"Review/Preview","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Applies completing the square to write graphing form and identify the vertex.","question_html":"<section class=\"problem\" id=\"8-106\">\n<h2>8-106</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Review/Preview</span> Sorted to Unit 6, Section 4: Completing the Square</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Applies completing the square to write graphing form and identify the vertex.</div>\n<p>For each quadratic function below, use the idea of completing the square to write it in graphing form. Then state the vertex of each parabola. <a class=\"etool-link\" href=\"https://technology.cpm.org/general/tiles/\" rel=\"noopener\" target=\"_blank\">8-106 HW eTool</a></p>\n<div class=\"two-col\"><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" type=\"a\"><li><p>$f(x)=x^2+6x+15$</p></li></ol></div><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"2\" type=\"a\"><li><p>$y=x^2-4x+9$</p></li></ol></div></div>\n<div class=\"two-col\"><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"3\" type=\"a\"><li><p>$f(x)=x^2+8x$</p></li></ol></div><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"4\" type=\"a\"><li><p>$y=x^2+5x-2$</p></li></ol></div></div>\n</section>","resources":[{"label":"8-106 HW eTool","href":"https://technology.cpm.org/general/tiles/"}]},{"problem_id":"unit06-0073","original_source":"cpm-9-14","source_lesson":"9.1.2","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"4","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 4: Choosing and Defending Solution Methods","source_type":"Lesson","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Compares factoring, completing the square, and the Quadratic Formula; method selection is central.","question_html":"<section class=\"problem\" id=\"9-14\">\n<h2>9-14</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Lesson</span> Sorted to Unit 6, Section 3: Quadratic Formula</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Compares quadratic-solving methods and connects the Quadratic Formula to solving a generic quadratic.</div>\n<div><p>The Quadratic Formula is only one of the tools you can use to solve quadratic equations.</p>\n<ol class=\"lower-alpha\" type=\"a\">\n<li><p>What are the other methods that you can use?</p></li>\n<li><p>You may be thinking, \u201cWhere did this formula come from? Why does it work?\u201d You can find the formula by starting with a generic quadratic $ax^2+bx+c=0$ and using your algebra skills to solve for $x$. See the Math Notes box for this lesson to learn about one way this formula can be derived. Later, in Chapter 10, you will learn another formal method to derive the Quadratic Formula.</p></li>\n</ol></div>\n</section>"},{"problem_id":"unit06-0074","original_source":"cpm-9-34","source_lesson":"9.1.4","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"4","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 4: Choosing and Defending Solution Methods","source_type":"Lesson","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Chooses efficient quadratic-solving strategies and switches methods when needed.","question_html":"<section class=\"problem\" id=\"9-34\">\n<h2>9-34</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Lesson</span> Sorted to Unit 6, Section 3: Quadratic Formula</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Chooses an efficient method for solving quadratic equations and switches methods when needed.</div>\n<div><p>Examine the quadratic equations below with your team. For each equation:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><p>Decide which strategy is best to try first.</p></li>\n<li><p>Solve the equation. If your first strategy does not work, switch to the other strategy.</p></li>\n<li><p>Check your solution(s).</p></li>\n</ul>\n<p>Be prepared to share your process with the class.</p>\n<div class=\"two-col\">\n<div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" type=\"a\"><li><p>$x^2+12x+27=0$</p></li></ol></div>\n<div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"2\" type=\"a\"><li><p>$0.5x^2+9x-2.8=6$</p></li></ol></div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"two-col\">\n<div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"3\" type=\"a\"><li><p>$(3x+4)(2x-1)=0$</p></li></ol></div>\n<div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"4\" type=\"a\"><li><p>$x^2+12=8x-4$</p></li></ol></div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"two-col\">\n<div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"5\" type=\"a\"><li><p>$x^2+5-2x=0$</p></li></ol></div>\n<div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"6\" type=\"a\"><li><p>$20x^2-30x=2x+45$</p></li></ol></div>\n</div></div>\n</section>"},{"problem_id":"unit06-0075","original_source":"cpm-9-35","source_lesson":"9.1.4","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"4","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 4: Choosing and Defending Solution Methods","source_type":"Learning Log","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Reflects on when to use factoring, completing the square, or the Quadratic Formula.","question_html":"<section class=\"problem\" id=\"9-35\">\n<h2>9-35</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Lesson</span> Sorted to Unit 6, Section 3: Quadratic Formula</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Reflects on when to use factoring, completing the square, or the Quadratic Formula.</div>\n<div><p><strong>Learning Log.</strong> With the class, decide when it is best to solve a quadratic by factoring or completing the square, and when you should go directly to the Quadratic Formula. Copy your observations in your Learning Log. Title this entry \u201cChoosing a Strategy to Solve Quadratics\u201d and include today's date.</p></div>\n</section>"},{"problem_id":"unit06-0076","original_source":"cpm-9-39","source_lesson":"9.1.4","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"4","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 4: Choosing and Defending Solution Methods","source_type":"Review/Preview","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Uses any appropriate quadratic-solving method; strategy selection dominates.","question_html":"<section class=\"problem\" id=\"9-39\">\n<h2>9-39</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Review/Preview</span> Sorted to Unit 6, Section 3: Quadratic Formula</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Solves quadratic equations using any appropriate method, including non-factorable cases.</div>\n<div><p>Solve the following quadratic equations using any method.</p>\n<div class=\"two-col\">\n<div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" type=\"a\"><li><p>$10000x^2-64=0$</p></li></ol></div>\n<div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"2\" type=\"a\"><li><p>$9x^2-8=-34x$</p></li></ol></div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"two-col\">\n<div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"3\" type=\"a\"><li><p>$2x^2-4x+7=0$</p></li></ol></div>\n<div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"4\" type=\"a\"><li><p>$3.2x+0.2x^2-5=0$</p></li></ol></div>\n</div></div>\n</section>"},{"problem_id":"unit06-0077","original_source":"cpm-9-117","source_lesson":"9.4.3","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"4","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 4: Choosing and Defending Solution Methods","source_type":"Review/Preview","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Solves the same quadratic by two methods and compares efficiency.","question_html":"<section class=\"problem\" id=\"9-117\">\n<h2>9-117</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Review/Preview</span> Sorted to Unit 6, Section 3: Quadratic Formula</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Solves the same quadratic using the Quadratic Formula and completing the square, then compares efficiency.</div>\n<div>\n<p>Solve the quadratic equation below <em>twice</em>, once using the Quadratic Formula and once by completing the square. Which was easier?</p>\n<p class=\"center\">$x^2-10x+21=-4$</p>\n</div>\n</section>"},{"problem_id":"unit06-0078","original_source":"cpm-CL9-125d","source_lesson":"Chapter 9 Closure","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"4","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 4: Choosing and Defending Solution Methods","source_type":"Closure","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Explicitly prescribed graphing method; method-selection category.","question_html":"<div class=\"card\" id=\"CL9125\">\n<div class=\"problem-title\">CL 9-125</div>\n<p>Solve each quadratic equation using the specified method.</p>\n<div class=\"grid-2\">\n<ol type=\"a\"><li><span class=\"method\">The Quadratic Formula</span><br/>$0=3x^2+4x-7$</li></ol>\n<ol start=\"2\" type=\"a\"><li><span class=\"method\">Factoring</span><br/>$x^2-3x-18=0$</li></ol>\n<ol start=\"3\" type=\"a\"><li><span class=\"method\">Completing the square</span><br/>$x^2+4x+1=0$</li></ol>\n<ol start=\"4\" type=\"a\"><li><span class=\"method\">Using a graph</span><br/>$2x^2+5x-12=0$</li></ol>\n</div>\n</div>"},{"problem_id":"unit06-0079","original_source":"cpm-10-14","source_lesson":"10.1.1","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"4","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 4: Choosing Methods","source_type":"Review/Preview","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Quadratics solved using method of choice; method selection dominates.","question_html":"<section class=\"problem\" id=\"10-14\">\n<h2>10-14</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Review/Preview</span> Sorted to Unit 6, Section 3: Quadratic Formula</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Solves quadratic equations using any method, including cases where the Quadratic Formula may be useful.</div>\n<div>\n<p>Solve for $x$ using the method of your choice.</p>\n<div class=\"two-col\"><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" type=\"a\"><li>$0=2x^2-5x-33$</li></ol></div><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"2\" type=\"a\"><li>$0=3x^2-4x-1$</li></ol></div></div>\n</div>\n</section>"},{"problem_id":"unit06-0080","original_source":"cpm-10-22","source_lesson":"10.2.1","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"4","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 4: Choosing Methods","source_type":"Lesson","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Rewrites a decimal quadratic into an easier equivalent form before solving by factoring.","question_html":"<section class=\"problem\" id=\"10-22\">\n<h2>10-22</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Lesson</span> Sorted to Unit 6, Section 1: Solving Quadratics by Factoring</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Rewrites a decimal quadratic into an equivalent equation with integer coefficients, then solves by factoring.</div>\n<p>Cassie wants to use the Zero Product Property to find the $x$-intercepts of the quadratic function $x^2+1.5x-2.5=y$. She started factoring. Suddenly, Claudia blurted out, <em>\u201cNo, Cassie! I think there is another way. Can\u2019t you first rewrite this equation so it has no decimals? Then it will be faster and easier to factor. And we won\u2019t have to use the Quadratic Formula!\u201d</em></p>\n<ol class=\"lower-alpha\" type=\"a\">\n<li>What is Claudia talking about? Explain what she means. Then rewrite the equation so that it has no decimals.</li>\n<li>Now solve the new equation, the one without decimals, by factoring. Check your solution(s).</li>\n</ol>\n</section>"},{"problem_id":"unit06-0081","original_source":"cpm-10-23","source_lesson":"10.2.1","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"4","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 4: Choosing Methods","source_type":"Lesson","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Equivalent-equation rewriting is the instructional focus.","question_html":"<section class=\"problem\" id=\"10-23\">\n<h2>10-23</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Lesson</span> Sorted to Unit 0A: Solving Equations</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Builds fluency with equivalent equations by clearing common factors, fractions, and decimals before solving.</div>\n<p><strong>SOLVING BY REWRITING</strong></p>\n<p>Rewriting $x^2+1.5x-2.5=0$ in problem 10-22 gave you a new, equivalent equation that was much easier to solve. If needed, refer to the Math Notes box for this lesson for more information about equivalent equations.</p>\n<p>How can each equation below be rewritten so that it is easier to solve? With your team, find an equivalent equation for each equation below. Be sure your equivalent equation has no fractions or decimals and has numbers that are reasonably small. Strive to find the <em>simplest</em> equation. Then solve the new equation and check your answer(s). Be sure to explain your reasoning for each step.</p>\n<div class=\"two-col\">\n<div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" type=\"a\"><li>$32(3x)-32(5)=32(7)$</li></ol></div>\n<div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"2\" type=\"a\"><li>$9000x^2-6000x-15000=0$</li></ol></div>\n<div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"3\" type=\"a\"><li>$\\frac{1}{3}+\\frac{x}{3}=\\frac{10}{3}$</li></ol></div>\n<div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"4\" type=\"a\"><li>$2x^2+4x-2.5=0$</li></ol></div>\n</div>\n</section>"},{"problem_id":"unit06-0082","original_source":"cpm-10-26","source_lesson":"10.2.1","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"4","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 4: Choosing Methods","source_type":"Lesson","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Generates and verifies equivalent equations.","question_html":"<section class=\"problem\" id=\"10-26\">\n<h2>10-26</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Lesson</span> Sorted to Other: Reflection / Study Skills</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Has students generate equivalent equations by reversing the simplifying process and justifying equivalence.</div>\n<p>Now you are going to reverse the process of solving equations by rewriting them. Your teacher will give your team a simple equation that you need to \u201ccomplicate.\u201d</p>\n<ol class=\"lower-alpha\" type=\"a\">\n<li>Change the equation to make it seem harder, although you know it is still equivalent to the easy equation.</li>\n<li>Verify that your new equation is equivalent to the one assigned by your teacher.</li>\n<li>Share your new equation with the class by posting it on the overhead projector or chalkboard.</li>\n<li>Copy down the equations generated by your class on another piece of paper. You will need these equations for homework problem 10-27.</li>\n</ol>\n</section>"},{"problem_id":"unit06-0083","original_source":"cpm-10-27","source_lesson":"10.2.1","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"4","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 4: Choosing Methods","source_type":"Review/Preview","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Solves equations generated through equivalent rewriting.","question_html":"<section class=\"problem\" id=\"10-27\">\n<h2>10-27</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Review/Preview</span> Sorted to Unit 0A: Solving Equations</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Solves peer-generated equivalent equations and checks solutions.</div>\n<p>Solve the equations generated by your class in problem 10-26. Be sure to check each solution and show all work.</p>\n</section>"},{"problem_id":"unit06-0084","original_source":"cpm-10-34","source_lesson":"10.2.2","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"4","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 4: Choosing Methods","source_type":"Lesson","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Fraction Busters / equivalent-equation strategy before solving.","question_html":"<section class=\"problem\" id=\"10-34\">\n<h2>10-34</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Lesson</span> Sorted to Unit 0A: Algebra Foundations Review</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Uses a common denominator to clear fractions and produce an equivalent equation before solving.</div>\n<p>Examine the equation below.</p>\n<p class=\"center\">$\\frac{x}{6}-\\frac{5}{8}=4$</p>\n<ol class=\"lower-alpha\" type=\"a\">\n<li>Multiply each term by $6$. What happened? Do any fractions remain?</li>\n<li>If you have not already done so, decide how you can change your result from part (a) so that no fractions remain. Then solve the resulting equation.</li>\n<li>Multiplying $\\frac{x}{6}-\\frac{5}{8}=4$ by $6$ did not eliminate all the fractions. What could you have multiplied by to get rid of all the fractions? Explain how you got your answer and write the equivalent equation that has no fractions.</li>\n<li>Solve the resulting equation from part (c) and check your solution in the original equation.</li>\n</ol>\n</section>"},{"problem_id":"unit06-0085","original_source":"cpm-10-35","source_lesson":"10.2.2","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"4","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 4: Choosing Methods","source_type":"Lesson","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Fraction Busters / equivalent-equation strategy before solving.","question_html":"<section class=\"problem\" id=\"10-35\">\n<h2>10-35</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Lesson</span> Sorted to Unit 0A: Algebra Foundations Review</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Applies Fraction Busters to eliminate fractions and solve a linear equation.</div>\n<p>Examine the equation below.</p>\n<p class=\"center\">$\\frac{5x}{3}+\\frac{15}{2}=\\frac{5}{2}$</p>\n<ol class=\"lower-alpha\" type=\"a\">\n<li>Solve the equation by first finding an equivalent equation without fractions. Check your solution(s).</li>\n<li>Often, this method of eliminating fractions from an equation is called <strong>Fraction Busters</strong> because the multiplication of the equation by a common denominator or several of the denominators eliminates, or \u201cbusts,\u201d the fractions. The result is an equation with no fractions.<p>By what number, or numbers, did you multiply both sides of the equation in part (a) to eliminate the fractions? How did you choose that number? Is it the smallest number that would eliminate all of the fractions?</p></li>\n</ol>\n</section>"},{"problem_id":"unit06-0086","original_source":"cpm-10-36","source_lesson":"10.2.2","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"4","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 4: Choosing Methods","source_type":"Lesson","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Fraction Busters / equivalent-equation strategy before solving.","question_html":"<section class=\"problem\" id=\"10-36\">\n<h2>10-36</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Lesson</span> Sorted to Unit 0A: Algebra Foundations Review</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Solves fractional and rational equations by clearing denominators, including cases with variable denominators.</div>\n<p>Work with your team to solve each of the equations below by first finding an equivalent equation that contains no fractions. Each problem presents new challenges and situations. Be ready to justify how you solved each problem and share why you did what you did with the class. Remember to check each solution.</p>\n<div class=\"two-col\">\n<div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" type=\"a\"><li>$\\frac{x}{4}-\\frac{x}{6}=\\frac{2}{3}$</li></ol></div>\n<div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"2\" type=\"a\"><li>$\\frac{5}{x}-2x=3$</li></ol></div>\n<div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"3\" type=\"a\"><li>$\\frac{-2x+1}{3}-\\frac{x+3}{7}=8$</li></ol></div>\n<div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"4\" type=\"a\"><li>$\\frac{x+3}{x}+2=\\frac{x+5}{x}$</li></ol></div>\n</div>\n</section>"},{"problem_id":"unit06-0087","original_source":"cpm-10-37","source_lesson":"10.2.2","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"4","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 4: Choosing Methods","source_type":"Lesson","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Fraction Busters / equivalent-equation strategy before solving.","question_html":"<section class=\"problem\" id=\"10-37\">\n<h2>10-37</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Lesson</span> Sorted to Solving Equations and Inequalities</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Identifies excluded values in rational equations before solving.</div>\n<p>Now examine parts (b) and (d) of problem 10-36. Before solving, could you already tell what values of $x$ were definitely not allowed?</p>\n</section>"},{"problem_id":"unit06-0088","original_source":"cpm-10-38","source_lesson":"10.2.2","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"4","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 4: Choosing Methods","source_type":"Lesson","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Fraction Busters / equivalent-equation strategy before solving.","question_html":"<section class=\"problem\" id=\"10-38\">\n<h2>10-38</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Lesson</span> Sorted to Unit 0A: Algebra Foundations Review</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Chooses equivalent forms to simplify quadratics, rational equations, decimals, and fractional linear equations before solving.</div>\n<p>Solve the equations below by first changing each equation to a simpler, equivalent equation. Check your solution(s). Are any values of the variable not allowed?</p>\n<div class=\"two-col\">\n<div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" type=\"a\"><li>$50x^2+200x=-150$</li></ol></div>\n<div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"2\" type=\"a\"><li>$\\frac{a}{9}+\\frac{1}{a}=\\frac{2}{3}$</li></ol></div>\n<div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"3\" type=\"a\"><li>$1.2m-0.2=3.8+m$</li></ol></div>\n<div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"4\" type=\"a\"><li>$\\frac{3x}{4}+\\frac{x}{3}-\\frac{1}{2}=0$</li></ol></div>\n</div>\n</section>"},{"problem_id":"unit06-0089","original_source":"cpm-10-39","source_lesson":"10.2.2","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"4","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 4: Choosing Methods","source_type":"Review/Preview","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Continues solving by rewriting and equivalent-equation construction.","question_html":"<section class=\"problem\" id=\"10-39\">\n<h2>10-39</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Review/Preview</span> Sorted to Unit 0A: Algebra Foundations Review</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Reviews solving by rewriting, including large coefficients, fractions, and a quadratic equation.</div>\n<p>Solve the equations below by first changing each equation to a simpler equivalent equation. Check your solutions.</p>\n<div class=\"two-col\">\n<div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" type=\"a\"><li>$3000x-2000=10{,}000$</li></ol></div>\n<div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"2\" type=\"a\"><li>$\\frac{x^2}{2}+\\frac{3x}{2}-5=0$</li></ol></div>\n<div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"3\" type=\"a\"><li>$\\frac{5}{2}x-\\frac{1}{3}=13$</li></ol></div>\n<div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"4\" type=\"a\"><li>$\\frac{3}{10}+\\frac{2x}{5}=\\frac{1}{2}$</li></ol></div>\n</div>\n</section>"},{"problem_id":"unit06-0090","original_source":"cpm-10-46","source_lesson":"10.2.3","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"4","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 4: Choosing Methods","source_type":"Lesson","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Compares or selects among rewriting, undoing, and looking-inside methods.","question_html":"<section class=\"problem\" id=\"10-46\">\n<h2>10-46</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Lesson</span> Sorted to Unit 0A: Algebra Foundations Review</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Introduces multiple equation-solving strategies using a simple linear equation as the common comparison.</div>\n<p><strong>Different Methods to Solve an Equation</strong></p>\n<p>In just a few more lessons you will be able to solve the equation $\\left(\\sqrt{|x+5|}-6\night)^2+4=20$. This equation is complex and will require you to look at solving an equation in new ways. To be prepared for other strange and unfamiliar equations, you will first examine all of the solving tools you currently have by solving a comparatively easier equation:</p>\n<p class=\"center\">$4(x+3)=20$</p>\n<p><strong>Your Task:</strong> With your team, solve $4(x+3)=20$ for $x$ in <em>at least</em> two different ways. Explain how you found $x$ in each case and be prepared to share your explanations with the class.</p>\n</section>"},{"problem_id":"unit06-0091","original_source":"cpm-10-47","source_lesson":"10.2.3","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"4","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 4: Choosing Methods","source_type":"Lesson","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Compares or selects among rewriting, undoing, and looking-inside methods.","question_html":"<section class=\"problem\" id=\"10-47\">\n<h2>10-47</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Lesson</span> Sorted to Unit 0A: Algebra Foundations Review</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Uses the distributive property as a rewriting strategy before solving a linear equation.</div>\n<p><strong>Solving by Rewriting</strong></p>\n<p>David wants to find $x$ in the equation $4(x+3)=20$. He said, \u201cI can rewrite this equation by distributing the $4$ on the left-hand side.\u201d After distributing, what should his new equation be? Solve this equation using David\u2019s method.</p>\n</section>"},{"problem_id":"unit06-0092","original_source":"cpm-10-48","source_lesson":"10.2.3","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"4","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 4: Choosing Methods","source_type":"Lesson","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Compares or selects among rewriting, undoing, and looking-inside methods.","question_html":"<section class=\"problem\" id=\"10-48\">\n<h2>10-48</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Lesson</span> Sorted to Unit 0A: Algebra Foundations Review</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Uses inverse operations to undo multiplication before solving a linear equation.</div>\n<p><strong>Solving by Undoing</strong></p>\n<p>Juan says, \u201cI see the whole thing a different way.\u201d Here is how he explains his approach to solving $4(x+3)=20$, which he calls \u201cundoing\u201d: \u201cInstead of distributing first, I want to eliminate the $4$ from the left side by undoing the multiplication.\u201d</p>\n<ol class=\"lower-alpha\" type=\"a\">\n<li>What can Juan do to both sides of the equation to remove the $4$? Why does this work?</li>\n<li>Solve the equation using Juan\u2019s method. Did you get the same result as David?</li>\n<li>Why is it appropriate for this method to be called \u201cundoing\u201d?</li>\n</ol>\n</section>"},{"problem_id":"unit06-0093","original_source":"cpm-10-49","source_lesson":"10.2.3","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"4","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 4: Choosing Methods","source_type":"Lesson","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Compares or selects among rewriting, undoing, and looking-inside methods.","question_html":"<section class=\"problem\" id=\"10-49\">\n<h2>10-49</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Lesson</span> Sorted to Unit 0A: Algebra Foundations Review</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Treats a grouped expression as a single quantity and solves by identifying what that group must equal.</div>\n<p><strong>Solving by Looking Inside</strong></p>\n<p>Kenya said, \u201cI solved David\u2019s equation in a much quicker way!\u201d She solved the equation $4(x+3)=20$ with an approach that she calls \u201clooking inside.\u201d Here is how she described her thinking: \u201cI think about everything inside the parentheses as a group. After all, the parentheses group all that stuff together. I think the contents of the parentheses must be $5$.\u201d</p>\n<ol class=\"lower-alpha\" type=\"a\">\n<li>Why must the expression inside the parentheses equal $5$?</li>\n<li>Write an equation that states that the contents of the parentheses must equal $5$. Then solve this equation. Did you get the same result as with David\u2019s method?</li>\n</ol>\n</section>"},{"problem_id":"unit06-0094","original_source":"cpm-10-50","source_lesson":"10.2.3","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"4","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 4: Choosing Methods","source_type":"Lesson","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Compares or selects among rewriting, undoing, and looking-inside methods.","question_html":"<section class=\"problem\" id=\"10-50\">\n<h2>10-50</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Lesson</span> Sorted to Unit 0A: Algebra Foundations Review</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Compares and names the three solving approaches: rewriting, looking inside, and undoing.</div>\n<p><strong>The Three Methods</strong></p>\n<ol class=\"lower-alpha\" type=\"a\">\n<li>Find the Math Notes box for this lesson and read it with your team.</li>\n<li>Match the names of approaches on the left with the examples on the right.</li>\n</ol>\n<div class=\"two-col\">\n<div>\n<ol>\n<li>Rewriting</li>\n<li>Looking inside</li>\n<li>Undoing</li>\n</ol>\n</div>\n<div>\n<ol class=\"lower-roman\" type=\"i\">\n<li>\u201cIf $3+(4n-4)=12$, then $(4n-4)$ must equal $9$\u2026\u201d</li>\n<li>\u201cSubtracting is the opposite of adding, so for the equation $3(x-7)+4=23$, I can start by subtracting $4$ from both sides\u2026\u201d</li>\n<li>\u201cThis problem might be easier if I turned $4(2x-3)$ into $8x-12$\u2026\u201d</li>\n</ol>\n</div>\n</div>\n</section>"},{"problem_id":"unit06-0095","original_source":"cpm-10-51","source_lesson":"10.2.3","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"4","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 4: Choosing Methods","source_type":"Lesson","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Compares or selects among rewriting, undoing, and looking-inside methods.","question_html":"<section class=\"problem\" id=\"10-51\">\n<h2>10-51</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Lesson</span> Sorted to Unit 0A: Algebra Foundations Review</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Requires choosing an efficient method among rewriting, looking inside, and undoing for equations involving fractions, radicals, and exponentials.</div>\n<p>For each equation below, decide whether it would be best to rewrite, look inside, or undo. Then solve the equation, showing your work and writing down the name of the approach you used. Check your solutions, if possible.</p>\n<div class=\"three-col\"><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" type=\"a\"><li>$\\frac{2x-8}{10}=6$</li></ol></div><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"2\" type=\"a\"><li>$4+(x\\div 3)=9$</li></ol></div><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"3\" type=\"a\"><li>$\\sqrt{3x+3}=6$</li></ol></div></div>\n<div class=\"three-col\"><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"4\" type=\"a\"><li>$7^{x+3}=7^{3x}$</li></ol></div><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"5\" type=\"a\"><li>$\\sqrt{x}+4=9$</li></ol></div><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"6\" type=\"a\"><li>$\\frac{x}{3}-\\frac{x}{9}=6$</li></ol></div></div>\n</section>"},{"problem_id":"unit06-0096","original_source":"cpm-10-52","source_lesson":"10.2.3","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"4","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 4: Choosing Methods","source_type":"Lesson","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Compares or selects among rewriting, undoing, and looking-inside methods.","question_html":"<section class=\"problem\" id=\"10-52\">\n<h2>10-52</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Lesson</span> Sorted to Unit 6, Section 2: Solving Quadratics with Graphs and Square Roots</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Solves a squared binomial equation and compares methods, emphasizing possible missed solutions when using \u201clooking inside.\u201d</div>\n<p>Consider the equation $(x-7)^2=9$.</p>\n<ol class=\"lower-alpha\" type=\"a\">\n<li>Solve this equation using <em>all three</em> approaches studied in this lesson. Make sure each team member solves the equation using all three approaches.</li>\n<li>Did you get the same solution using all three approaches? If not, why not?</li>\n<li>Of the three methods, which do you think was the most efficient method for this problem? Why?</li>\n</ol>\n</section>"},{"problem_id":"unit06-0097","original_source":"cpm-10-54","source_lesson":"10.2.3","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"4","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 4: Choosing Methods","source_type":"Review/Preview","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Fraction-busting equivalent-equation strategy.","question_html":"<section class=\"problem\" id=\"10-54\">\n<h2>10-54</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Review/Preview</span> Sorted to Unit 0A: Algebra Foundations Review</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Uses a fraction-busting equivalent equation to solve a linear equation with small fractions.</div>\n<p>For the equation $\\frac{3}{200}+\\frac{x}{50}=\\frac{7}{100}$:</p>\n<ol class=\"lower-alpha\" type=\"a\">\n<li>Find a simpler equivalent equation (i.e., an equivalent equation with no fractions) and solve for $x$.</li>\n<li>Which method listed in this lesson's Math Notes box did you use in part (a)?</li>\n</ol>\n</section>"},{"problem_id":"unit06-0098","original_source":"cpm-10-67","source_lesson":"10.2.4","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"4","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 4: Choosing Methods","source_type":"Review/Preview","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Mixed equation-solving requiring method selection.","question_html":"<section class=\"problem\" id=\"10-67\">\n<h2>10-67</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Review/Preview</span> Sorted to Unit 0A: Algebra Foundations Review</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Mixed equation-solving review with square roots, rational expressions, and linear equations.</div>\n<p>Solve these equations, if possible. Each time, be sure you have found all possible solutions. Check your work and write down the name of the method(s) you used.</p>\n<div class=\"two-col\"><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" type=\"a\"><li>$\\left(x+4\\right)^2=49$</li></ol></div><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"2\" type=\"a\"><li>$3\\sqrt{x+2}=12$</li></ol></div></div>\n<div class=\"two-col\"><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"3\" type=\"a\"><li>$\\frac{2}{x}+\\frac{3}{10}=\\frac{13}{10}$</li></ol></div><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"4\" type=\"a\"><li>$5\\left(2x-1\\right)-2=13$</li></ol></div></div>\n</section>"},{"problem_id":"unit06-0099","original_source":"cpm-10-83","source_lesson":"10.2.5","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"4","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 4: Choosing Methods","source_type":"Review/Preview","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Mixed solving review requiring strategy selection.","question_html":"<section class=\"problem\" id=\"10-83\">\n<h2>10-83</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Review/Preview</span> Sorted to Unit 0A: Algebra Foundations Review</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Mixed equation-solving review that includes exponent rewriting, fraction busters, and square-root/quadratic structure.</div>\n<p>Solve each equation by first rewriting it in a more useful form.</p>\n<div class=\"two-col\"><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" type=\"a\"><li>$25^2=125^{x+1}$</li></ol></div><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"2\" type=\"a\"><li>$\\frac{x}{5}+\\frac{x-1}{3}=2$</li></ol></div></div>\n<div class=\"two-col\"><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"3\" type=\"a\"><li>$x^2-4x+4=25$</li></ol></div><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"4\" type=\"a\"><li>$9^x=\\left(\\frac{1}{3}\\right)^{x+3}$</li></ol></div></div>\n</section>"},{"problem_id":"unit06-0100","original_source":"cpm-10-88","source_lesson":"10.2.6","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"4","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 4: Choosing Methods","source_type":"Lesson","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Mixed absolute value, radical, quadratic, cubic, and exponential equations.","question_html":"<section class=\"problem\" id=\"10-88\">\n<h2>10-88</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Lesson</span> Sorted to Unit 0A: Solving Equations</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Mixed equation-solving practice using rewriting, looking inside, and undoing across absolute value, radical, quadratic, cubic, and exponential equations.</div>\n<p>Solve these equations. Each time, be sure you have found all possible solutions. Check your work and write down the name of the method(s) you used.</p>\n<div class=\"three-col\"><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" type=\"a\"><li>$|4x+20|=8$</li></ol></div><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"2\" type=\"a\"><li>$(x-13)^3=8$</li></ol></div><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"3\" type=\"a\"><li>$2\\sqrt{x-4}=14$</li></ol></div></div>\n<div class=\"three-col\"><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"4\" type=\"a\"><li>$6|x-8|-4=14$</li></ol></div><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"5\" type=\"a\"><li>$3(x+12)^2=27$</li></ol></div><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"6\" type=\"a\"><li>$6^{x+9}=36^x$</li></ol></div></div>\n</section>"},{"problem_id":"unit06-0101","original_source":"cpm-10-92","source_lesson":"10.2.6","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"4","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 4: Choosing Methods","source_type":"Review/Preview","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Mixed solving strategies.","question_html":"<section class=\"problem\" id=\"10-92\">\n<h2>10-92</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Review/Preview</span> Sorted to Unit 0A: Solving Equations</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Mixed solving review with square-root, absolute-value, and quadratic-structure equations, including a no-solution case.</div>\n<p>Solve these equations, if possible. Be sure to find all possible solutions. Check your work and write down the name of the method(s) you used.</p>\n<div class=\"two-col\"><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" type=\"a\"><li>$9(x-4)^2=81$</li></ol></div><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"2\" type=\"a\"><li>$|x-6|=2$</li></ol></div></div>\n<div class=\"two-col\"><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"3\" type=\"a\"><li>$5=2+\\sqrt{3x}$</li></ol></div><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"4\" type=\"a\"><li>$2|x+1|=-4$</li></ol></div></div>\n</section>"},{"problem_id":"unit06-0102","original_source":"cpm-10-124","source_lesson":"10.3.2","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"4","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 4: Choosing Methods","source_type":"Review/Preview","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Quadratics solved using any chosen method.","question_html":"<section class=\"problem\" id=\"10-124\">\n<h2>10-124</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Review/Preview</span> Sorted to Unit 6, Section 3: Quadratic Formula</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Solves quadratic equations using any method, including a case with non-real complex solutions.</div>\n<p>Solve each quadratic equation below using any method you choose. Check your solutions.</p>\n<div class=\"two-col\"><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" type=\"a\"><li>$(5x-1)(x+3)=0$</li></ol></div><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"2\" type=\"a\"><li>$4x^2+10x-6=0$</li></ol></div><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"3\" type=\"a\"><li>$x^2+2x+5=0$</li></ol></div><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"4\" type=\"a\"><li>$x^2+5x=14$</li></ol></div></div>\n</section>"},{"problem_id":"unit06-0103","original_source":"cpm-10-135","source_lesson":"10.3.3","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"4","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 4: Choosing Methods","source_type":"Lesson","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Complex equation requiring sequencing multiple solving techniques.","question_html":"<section class=\"problem\" id=\"10-135\">\n<h2>10-135</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Lesson</span> Sorted to Other: Solving Equations and Inequalities</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Pulls together square roots, absolute value, and quadratic structure in a complex equation-solving task.</div>\n<p><strong>Pulling it together.</strong> Now that you have the skills necessary to solve many interesting equations and inequalities, work with your team to solve the equation below. Show your solutions on a number line and be prepared to share your solving process with the class.</p>\n<p class=\"center\">$$(\\sqrt{|x+5|}-6)^2+4=20$$</p>\n</section>"},{"problem_id":"unit06-0104","original_source":"cpm-10-141","source_lesson":"10.3.3","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"4","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 4: Choosing Methods","source_type":"Review/Preview","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Mixed equation and inequality review requiring strategy selection.","question_html":"<section class=\"problem\" id=\"10-141\">\n<h2>10-141</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Review/Preview</span> Sorted to Other: Solving Equations and Inequalities</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Mixed equation and inequality practice across linear equations, quadratic inequalities, and absolute-value inequalities.</div>\n<p>Solve the equations and inequalities below. Check your solution(s), if possible.</p>\n<div class=\"two-col\"><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" type=\"a\"><li>$300x-1500=2400$</li></ol></div><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"2\" type=\"a\"><li>$\\frac{3}{2}x=\\frac{5}{6}x+2$</li></ol></div><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"3\" type=\"a\"><li>$x^2-25\\le 0$</li></ol></div><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"4\" type=\"a\"><li>$|3x-2|&gt;4$</li></ol></div></div>\n</section>"},{"problem_id":"unit06-0105","original_source":"cpm-CL10-143a","source_lesson":"Chapter 10 Closure","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"4","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 4: Choosing Methods","source_type":"Closure","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Fraction equation solved using equivalent-equation techniques.","question_html":"<div class=\"card\" id=\"CL10143\">\n<div class=\"problem-title\">CL 10-143</div>\n<p>Solve the equations below using any method. How many solutions does each problem have?</p>\n<div class=\"grid-2\">\n<ol type=\"a\"><li>$\\frac{x}{2}+\\frac{x}{3}=2$</li></ol>\n<ol start=\"2\" type=\"a\"><li>$\\sqrt{x-5}+10=15$</li></ol>\n<ol start=\"3\" type=\"a\"><li>$|x-7|=22$</li></ol>\n<ol start=\"4\" type=\"a\"><li>$(3x+7)^2=144$</li></ol>\n</div>\n</div>"},{"problem_id":"unit06-0106","original_source":"cpm-CL10-143b","source_lesson":"Chapter 10 Closure","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"4","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 4: Choosing Methods","source_type":"Closure","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Radical equation solved using appropriate strategy selection.","question_html":"<div class=\"card\" id=\"CL10143\">\n<div class=\"problem-title\">CL 10-143</div>\n<p>Solve the equations below using any method. How many solutions does each problem have?</p>\n<div class=\"grid-2\">\n<ol type=\"a\"><li>$\\frac{x}{2}+\\frac{x}{3}=2$</li></ol>\n<ol start=\"2\" type=\"a\"><li>$\\sqrt{x-5}+10=15$</li></ol>\n<ol start=\"3\" type=\"a\"><li>$|x-7|=22$</li></ol>\n<ol start=\"4\" type=\"a\"><li>$(3x+7)^2=144$</li></ol>\n</div>\n</div>"},{"problem_id":"unit06-0107","original_source":"cpm-CL10-143c","source_lesson":"Chapter 10 Closure","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"4","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 4: Choosing Methods","source_type":"Closure","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Absolute-value equation solved using appropriate strategy.","question_html":"<div class=\"card\" id=\"CL10143\">\n<div class=\"problem-title\">CL 10-143</div>\n<p>Solve the equations below using any method. How many solutions does each problem have?</p>\n<div class=\"grid-2\">\n<ol type=\"a\"><li>$\\frac{x}{2}+\\frac{x}{3}=2$</li></ol>\n<ol start=\"2\" type=\"a\"><li>$\\sqrt{x-5}+10=15$</li></ol>\n<ol start=\"3\" type=\"a\"><li>$|x-7|=22$</li></ol>\n<ol start=\"4\" type=\"a\"><li>$(3x+7)^2=144$</li></ol>\n</div>\n</div>"},{"problem_id":"unit06-0108","original_source":"cpm-CL10-143d","source_lesson":"Chapter 10 Closure","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"4","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 4: Choosing Methods","source_type":"Closure","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Perfect-square equation solved using a chosen method.","question_html":"<div class=\"card\" id=\"CL10143\">\n<div class=\"problem-title\">CL 10-143</div>\n<p>Solve the equations below using any method. How many solutions does each problem have?</p>\n<div class=\"grid-2\">\n<ol type=\"a\"><li>$\\frac{x}{2}+\\frac{x}{3}=2$</li></ol>\n<ol start=\"2\" type=\"a\"><li>$\\sqrt{x-5}+10=15$</li></ol>\n<ol start=\"3\" type=\"a\"><li>$|x-7|=22$</li></ol>\n<ol start=\"4\" type=\"a\"><li>$(3x+7)^2=144$</li></ol>\n</div>\n</div>"},{"problem_id":"unit06-0109","original_source":"cpm-CL10-147","source_lesson":"Chapter 10 Closure","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"4","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 4: Choosing Methods","source_type":"Closure","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Quadratics solved by any valid method; solution classification included.","question_html":"<div class=\"card\" id=\"CL10147\">\n<div class=\"problem-title\">CL 10-147</div>\n<p>Solve each quadratic equation using any method. Describe the answers as rational or irrational numbers.</p>\n<div class=\"grid-2\">\n<ol type=\"a\"><li>$2x^2-x-5=0$</li></ol>\n<ol start=\"2\" type=\"a\"><li>$4x^2=4x-1$</li></ol>\n</div>\n</div>"},{"problem_id":"unit06-0110","original_source":"cpm-11-5","source_lesson":"11.1.1","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"4","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 4: Choosing Methods","source_type":"Review/Preview","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Mixed linear, quadratic, absolute-value, rational equations and inequalities; strategy selection dominates.","question_html":"<section class=\"problem\" id=\"11-5\">\n<h2>11-5</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Review/Preview</span> Sorted to Other: Solving Equations and Inequalities</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Solves a mixed set of linear, quadratic, absolute-value, and rational equations/inequalities.</div>\n<p>Solve the equations and inequalities below. If necessary, write your solutions in approximate decimal form.</p><div class=\"four-col\"><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" type=\"a\"><li>$900x-200=500x+600$</li></ol></div><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"2\" type=\"a\"><li>$3k^2-15k+14=0$</li></ol></div><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"3\" type=\"a\"><li>$\\left|x-4\\right|&lt;6$</li></ol></div><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"4\" type=\"a\"><li>$\\frac{7}{3}+\\frac{x}{2}=\\frac{6x-1}{6}$</li></ol></div></div>\n</section>"},{"problem_id":"unit06-0111","original_source":"cpm-11-30","source_lesson":"11.2.1","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"4","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 4: Choosing Methods","source_type":"Review/Preview","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Mixed radical, absolute-value, rational, power equations and inequalities; method selection dominates.","question_html":"<section class=\"problem\" id=\"11-30\">\n<h2>11-30</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Review/Preview</span> Sorted to Other: Solving Equations and Inequalities</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Solves a mixed set of radical, absolute-value, rational, and power equations/inequalities.</div>\n<p>Solve the equations and inequalities below, if possible.</p>\n<div class=\"three-col\"><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" type=\"a\"><li>$\\sqrt{x-1}+13=13$</li></ol></div><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"2\" type=\"a\"><li>$6|x|&gt;18$</li></ol></div><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"3\" type=\"a\"><li>$|3x-2|\\le 2$</li></ol></div></div>\n<div class=\"three-col\"><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"4\" type=\"a\"><li>$\\frac{4}{5}-\\frac{2x}{3}=\\frac{3}{10}$</li></ol></div><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"5\" type=\"a\"><li>$(4x-2)^2\\le 100$</li></ol></div><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"6\" type=\"a\"><li>$(x-1)^3=8$</li></ol></div></div>\n</section>"},{"problem_id":"unit06-0112","original_source":"cpm-11-38","source_lesson":"11.2.1","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"4","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 4: Choosing Methods","source_type":"Review/Preview","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Mixed equation and inequality solving requiring multiple strategies.","question_html":"<section class=\"problem\" id=\"11-38\">\n<h2>11-38</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Review/Preview</span> Sorted to Other: Solving Equations and Inequalities</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Solves a mixed set of inequalities and equations and represents solutions on number lines.</div>\n<p>Solve the inequalities and equations below, if possible. Represent your solution on a number line.</p>\n<div class=\"three-col\"><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" type=\"a\"><li>$|x|+3&lt;5$</li></ol></div><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"2\" type=\"a\"><li>$5(2x+1)\\ge 30$</li></ol></div><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"3\" type=\"a\"><li>$\\frac{1}{x}-\\frac{5}{2}=\\frac{3}{2}$</li></ol></div></div>\n<div class=\"three-col\"><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"4\" type=\"a\"><li>$-5-x&gt;3-x$</li></ol></div><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"5\" type=\"a\"><li>$3\\sqrt{4-x}+1=13$</li></ol></div><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"6\" type=\"a\"><li>$|x+1|\\le 4$</li></ol></div></div>\n</section>"},{"problem_id":"unit06-0113","original_source":"cpm-11-71","source_lesson":"11.2.3","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"4","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 4: Choosing Methods","source_type":"Review/Preview","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Mixed absolute-value, quadratic, and rational equations/inequalities; method selection dominates.","question_html":"<section class=\"problem\" id=\"11-71\">\n<h2>11-71</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Review/Preview</span> Sorted to Other: Solving Equations and Inequalities</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Solves a mixed set of absolute value, quadratic, and rational equations/inequalities.</div>\n<p>Solve the equations and inequalities below. Check your solutions, if possible.</p>\n<div class=\"two-col\"><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" type=\"a\"><li>$|5x+8| \\ge -4$</li><li>$x^2+x-20&lt;0$</li></ol></div><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"3\" type=\"a\"><li>$2x^2-6x=-5$</li><li>$\\frac{5}{9}-\\frac{x}{3}=\\frac{4}{9}$</li></ol></div></div>\n</section>"},{"problem_id":"unit06-0114","original_source":"cpm-11-83","source_lesson":"11.3.1","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"4","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 4: Choosing Methods","source_type":"Review/Preview","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Mixed quadratic, absolute-value, and cubic equations/inequalities; method selection dominates.","question_html":"<section class=\"problem\" id=\"11-83\">\n<h2>11-83</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Review/Preview</span> Sorted to Other: Solving Equations and Inequalities</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Solves mixed quadratic, absolute-value inequality, and cubic equations.</div>\n<p>Solve each equation or inequality below, if possible. Check your solution.</p>\n<div class=\"three-col\"><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" type=\"a\"><li>$-(x-3)(x+1)=4$</li></ol></div><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"2\" type=\"a\"><li>$10|x-3|&gt;40$</li></ol></div><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"3\" type=\"a\"><li>$(x-5)^3=8$</li></ol></div></div></section>"},{"problem_id":"unit06-0115","original_source":"cpm-11-111","source_lesson":"11.3.4","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"4","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 4: Choosing Methods","source_type":"Review/Preview","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Mixed square-root and factored quadratic equations; method selection dominates.","question_html":"<section class=\"problem\" id=\"11-111\">\n<h2>11-111</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Review/Preview</span> Sorted to Other: Solving Equations and Inequalities</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Solves equations involving a square root equation and a factored quadratic equation.</div>\n<p>Solve each equation.</p><div class=\"two-col\"><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" type=\"a\"><li>$\\sqrt{y^2+5}=3$</li></ol></div><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"2\" type=\"a\"><li>$(x+3)(x-2)=6(x+3)$</li></ol></div></div>\n</section>"},{"problem_id":"unit06-0116","original_source":"cpm-11-119","source_lesson":"11.3.4","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"4","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 4: Choosing Methods","source_type":"Review/Preview","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Mixed rational, absolute-value, quadratic, and inequality solving; strategy selection dominates.","question_html":"<section class=\"problem\" id=\"11-119\">\n<h2>11-119</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Review/Preview</span> Sorted to Other: Solving Equations and Inequalities</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Solves a mixed set of equations and inequalities, including rational, radical-style, absolute-value, and quadratic forms.</div>\n<p>Solve the equations and inequalities below. Write your solutions in exact form.</p><div class=\"two-col\"><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" type=\"a\"><li>$\\frac{3}{4}-\\frac{x}{3}=\\frac{7-x}{4}$</li></ol></div><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"2\" type=\"a\"><li>$(b-4)^2&lt;12$</li></ol></div></div><div class=\"two-col\"><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"3\" type=\"a\"><li>$|3+x|-9\\le 21$</li></ol></div><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"4\" type=\"a\"><li>$5n^2-11n+2=0$</li></ol></div></div>\n</section>"},{"problem_id":"unit06-0117","original_source":"cpm-11-128","source_lesson":"11.3.5","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"4","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 4: Choosing Methods","source_type":"Review/Preview","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Solves same quadratic by completing the square, factoring, and Quadratic Formula; method comparison dominates.","question_html":"<section class=\"problem\" id=\"11-128\">\n<h2>11-128</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Review/Preview</span> Sorted to Unit 6, Section 3: Quadratic Formula</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Solves the same quadratic using completing the square, factoring, and the Quadratic Formula.</div>\n<p>Solve the quadratic equation below three times: once by completing the square, once by factoring and using the Zero Product Property, and once by using the Quadratic Formula. Make sure you get the same answer using both methods!</p><p class=\"center\">$x^2+14x+40=-5$</p>\n</section>"},{"problem_id":"unit06-0118","original_source":"cpm-11-132","source_lesson":"11.3.5","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"4","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 4: Choosing Methods","source_type":"Review/Preview","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Determines whether a value satisfies equations and inequalities from multiple families; strategy recognition dominates.","question_html":"<section class=\"problem\" id=\"11-132\">\n<h2>11-132</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Review/Preview</span> Sorted to Other: Solving Equations and Inequalities</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Checks whether a value satisfies several equations and inequalities.</div>\n<p><strong>Multiple Choice:</strong> For which of the following equations or inequalities is $x=-1$ a solution?</p><div class=\"two-col\"><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" type=\"a\"><li>$\\left(x+3\\right)^2&gt;4$</li><li>$\\frac{x+5}{2}=2x^2$</li></ol></div><div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"3\" type=\"a\"><li>$\\sqrt{x+6}=25$</li><li>$x^2+5x+6=0$</li></ol></div></div>\n</section>"},{"problem_id":"unit06-0119","original_source":"cpm-6-106","source_lesson":"6.2.5","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"5","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 5: Quadratic Modeling","source_type":"Lesson","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Fits a quadratic regression model and compares residual behavior against the linear model.","question_html":"<section class=\"problem\" id=\"6-106\">\n<h2>6-106</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Lesson</span> Sorted to Unit 6, Section 5: Quadratic Modeling</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Fits a quadratic regression model and compares residual behavior against the linear model.</div>\n<div><div><p> A BETTER MODEL</p><p>The residual plot in the previous problem suggested that you should consider a non-linear model to represent the data. You will fit a curve to the data in this problem. \t</p><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" type=\"a\"><li><p>Thinking about the relationship between the weight and the area, why is it reasonable to assume that a quadratic equation will model this relationship better? </p></li><li><p>Use your calculator or <a class=\"etool-link\" href=\"https://www.desmos.com/calculator/z6nwteghbo\" rel=\"noopener\" target=\"_blank\">6-106 Student eTool</a><em> </em>to find the quadratic regression curve equation. Add this graph to the scatterplot sketch. Be sure to label the graph with the equation. Click in the lower right corner of the graph to view it in full-screen mode.  \t\t</p><p>Note that the value of <em>R</em><sup>2</sup> for a curved model cannot directly be compared to the <em>R</em><sup>2</sup> from the linear model. The two values of <em>R</em><sup>2</sup> are computed differently.  </p></li><li><p>Based on the calculator display, which model is a better fit for the data?  </p></li><li><p>Make a residual plot for the quadratic regression. Compare the residual plot from the linear regression to the residual plot from the quadratic regression. Which model is a better fit for the data? </p></li></ol></div><p><img alt=\"Figure for 6-106\" class=\"figure-img\" src=\"assets/6-106.png\"/></p></div>\n</section>","resources":[{"label":"6-106 Student eTool","href":"https://www.desmos.com/calculator/z6nwteghbo"}]},{"problem_id":"unit06-0120","original_source":"cpm-8-89","source_lesson":"8.2.4","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"5","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 5: Quadratic Modeling","source_type":"Lesson","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Builds quadratic rules from tables using zeros, symmetry, and patterns in quadratic data.","question_html":"<section class=\"problem\" id=\"8-89\">\n<h2>8-89</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Lesson</span> Sorted to Unit 6, Section 5: Quadratic Modeling</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Writes quadratic rules from tables by using zeros, symmetry, and patterns in quadratic data.</div>\n<div><p><strong>TABLE TO RULE</strong></p>\n<p>You know how to make a table for a quadratic rule, but how can you write an equation when given the table? Examine this new connection that requires you to reverse your understanding of the Zero Product Property as you find a rule for each table below. What clues in the tables helped you find the rule? How can you check your equation using your graphing calculator?</p>\n<ol class=\"lower-alpha\" type=\"a\">\n<li><table><tr><th>$x$</th><td>$-4$</td><td>$-3$</td><td>$-2$</td><td>$-1$</td><td>$0$</td><td>$1$</td><td>$2$</td><td>$3$</td><td>$4$</td></tr><tr><th>$y$</th><td>$6$</td><td>$0$</td><td>$-4$</td><td>$-6$</td><td>$-6$</td><td>$-4$</td><td>$0$</td><td>$6$</td><td>$14$</td></tr></table></li>\n<li><table><tr><th>$x$</th><td>$-6$</td><td>$-5$</td><td>$-4$</td><td>$-3$</td><td>$-2$</td><td>$-1$</td><td>$0$</td><td>$1$</td><td>$2$</td><td>$3$</td><td>$4$</td></tr><tr><th>$y$</th><td>$7$</td><td>$0$</td><td>$-5$</td><td>$-8$</td><td>$-9$</td><td>$-8$</td><td>$-5$</td><td>$0$</td><td>$7$</td><td>$16$</td><td>$27$</td></tr></table></li>\n</ol></div>\n</section>"},{"problem_id":"unit06-0121","original_source":"cpm-8-90","source_lesson":"8.2.4","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"5","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 5: Quadratic Modeling","source_type":"Lesson","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Determines how much information is needed to specify a parabola and communicates model requirements.","question_html":"<section class=\"problem\" id=\"8-90\">\n<h2>8-90</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Lesson</span> Sorted to Unit 6, Section 5: Quadratic Modeling</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Determines how much information is needed to specify a parabola and communicates equations from intercept and graph information.</div>\n<div><p><strong>QUALITY CONTROL, Part One</strong></p>\n<p>Congratulations! With your promotion, you are now the Quality Assurance Representative of the Function Factory. Your job is to make sure your clients are happy. Whenever a client writes to the company, you must reply with clear directions that will solve his or her problem.</p>\n<p>Your boss has provided graphing technology and a team of fellow employees to help you fulfill your job description.</p>\n<p><strong>Your Task:</strong></p>\n<ol><li><p>Carefully read the complaints below. Use your graphing calculator to study each situation. Work with your team to resolve each situation.</p></li><li><p>Write each customer a friendly response that offers a solution to his or her problem. Remember that the customers are not parabola experts! Do not assume that they know anything about parabolas.</p></li></ol>\n<img alt=\"Three customer complaint letters about ordering parabolas, including intercept conditions and one sketched downward parabola.\" class=\"wide-img\" src=\"assets/8-90.png\"/></div>\n</section>"},{"problem_id":"unit06-0122","original_source":"cpm-8-91","source_lesson":"8.2.4","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"5","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 5: Quadratic Modeling","source_type":"Lesson","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Writes quadratic models from graph, intercept, vertex, and table information.","question_html":"<section class=\"problem\" id=\"8-91\">\n<h2>8-91</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Lesson</span> Sorted to Unit 6, Section 5: Quadratic Modeling</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Writes quadratic models in factored and standard form from a graph, intercepts, vertex information, and a table.</div>\n<div><p><strong>MORE CONNECTIONS</strong></p>\n<p>A journalist from the school newspaper wants to publish the results from the water-balloon contest. She wants a rule for each toss so that she can program her computer to create a graph for her article. You already have a rule for the toss made by Maggie from problem 8-55.</p>\n<div class=\"two-col\"><div>\n<ol class=\"lower-alpha\" type=\"a\"><li><p>The journalist knows that the factored form of an equation is <em>$y=a(x+b)(x+c)$</em>. What do <em>$b$</em> and <em>$c$</em> represent in the factored form?</p></li><li><p>Examine the graph at right that represents the height of Jen\u2019s toss. The journalist found the rule for this parabola was <em>$y=a(x-0)(x-8)$</em>, but did not know what value <em>$a$</em> was. Explain to the journalist how she could find the value of <em>$a$</em>.</p></li><li><p>If you have not already done so, find the equation for Jen\u2019s toss. Write it in factored form and standard form, and check by graphing it on your calculator.</p></li><li><p>Al released his balloon from the $10$-yard line, and it landed at the $16$-yard line. If the ball reached a height of $27$ yards, what equation represents the path of his toss?</p></li><li><p>Remember Imp\u2019s water-balloon toss? Since the water balloon was thrown on the computer, you were given only a table of data, shown again below. Find a rule that represents the height of Imp\u2019s balloon as it traveled through the air.</p>\n<table><tr><th>$x$ (yards)</th><td>$2$</td><td>$3$</td><td>$4$</td><td>$5$</td><td>$6$</td><td>$7$</td><td>$8$</td><td>$9$</td></tr><tr><th>$y$ (yards)</th><td>$0$</td><td>$9$</td><td>$16$</td><td>$21$</td><td>$24$</td><td>$25$</td><td>$24$</td><td>$21$</td></tr></table></li></ol>\n</div><div><img alt=\"Jen's water-balloon height graph, a downward-opening parabola with x-intercepts at 0 and 8 and vertex near (4,32).\" class=\"tall-img\" src=\"assets/8-91.png\"/></div></div></div>\n</section>"},{"problem_id":"unit06-0123","original_source":"cpm-8-92","source_lesson":"8.2.4","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"5","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 5: Quadratic Modeling","source_type":"Review/Preview","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Determines possible quadratic equations from sketched parabolas and key features.","question_html":"<section class=\"problem\" id=\"8-92\">\n<h2>8-92</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Review/Preview</span> Sorted to Unit 6, Section 5: Quadratic Modeling</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Determines possible quadratic equations from sketched parabolas and key features.</div>\n<div><p><strong>QUALITY CONTROL, Part Two</strong></p>\n<p>Lots O\u2019Dough, a wealthy customer, would like to order a variety of parabolas. However, he is feeling pressed for time and said that he will pay you lots of extra money if you complete his order for him. Of course you agreed! He sent you sketches of each parabola that he would like to receive. Determine a possible equation for each parabola so that you can pass this information on to the Manufacturing Department. <a class=\"etool-link\" href=\"https://www.desmos.com/calculator/peqjls3f15\" rel=\"noopener\" target=\"_blank\">8-92 HW eTool</a></p>\n<img alt=\"Four sketched parabolas labeled a through d with intercept or vertex information shown on the graphs.\" class=\"wide-img\" src=\"assets/8-92.png\"/></div>\n</section>","resources":[{"label":"8-92 HW eTool","href":"https://www.desmos.com/calculator/peqjls3f15"}]},{"problem_id":"unit06-0124","original_source":"cpm-9-26","source_lesson":"9.1.3","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"5","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 5: Quadratic Modeling","source_type":"Lesson","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Gateway Arch quadratic model; interprets intercepts, width, height, and context.","question_html":"<section class=\"problem\" id=\"9-26\">\n<h2>9-26</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Lesson</span> Sorted to Unit 6, Section 5: Quadratic Modeling</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Uses a quadratic model of an arch to find intercepts, width, height, and a contextual sketch.</div>\n<div><p><strong>THE SAINT LOUIS GATEWAY ARCH</strong></p>\n<p>Arches, like the Saint Louis Gateway Arch, are not parabolas. But sometimes arches can be <em>modeled</em> by a parabola so that predictions are possible. Suppose the Gateway Arch can be modeled by $y=630-0.00635x^2$, where both $x$ and $y$ represent distances in feet and the origin is the point on the ground directly below the arch's apex, its highest point.</p>\n<ol class=\"lower-alpha\" type=\"a\">\n<li><p>Find the $x$-intercepts of the Gateway Arch. What does this information tell you? Use a calculator to evaluate your answers.</p></li>\n<li><p>How wide is the arch at its base?</p></li>\n<li><p>How tall is the arch? How did you find your solution?</p></li>\n<li><p>Draw a quick sketch of the arch on graph paper, labeling the axes with all of the values you know.</p></li>\n</ol></div>\n</section>"},{"problem_id":"unit06-0125","original_source":"cpm-9-29","source_lesson":"9.1.3","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"5","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 5: Quadratic Modeling","source_type":"Review/Preview","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Creates quadratic equations from graph and table information; model construction dominates.","question_html":"<section class=\"problem\" id=\"9-29\">\n<h2>9-29</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Review/Preview</span> Sorted to Unit 5, Section 4: Graphing Quadratic Functions</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Finds quadratic equations from a graph and from a table of values. | Images: figures/9-29.png</div>\n<div><p>Find the equation that represents the information given below.</p>\n<figure class=\"figure\"><img alt=\"Problem 9-29 graph and table for finding quadratic equations\" src=\"assets/9-29.png\"/><figcaption>Problem 9-29</figcaption></figure></div>\n</section>"},{"problem_id":"unit06-0126","original_source":"cpm-9-30","source_lesson":"9.1.3","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"5","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 5: Quadratic Modeling","source_type":"Review/Preview","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Rectangle-area context leading to a quadratic model and realistic solution.","question_html":"<section class=\"problem\" id=\"9-30\">\n<h2>9-30</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Review/Preview</span> Sorted to Unit 6, Section 5: Quadratic Modeling</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Models a rectangle area situation with a quadratic equation and interprets the valid width.</div>\n<div><p>Solve the following problem using any method. Write your solution as a sentence.</p>\n<p>The length of a rectangle is $5$ cm longer than twice the length of the width. If the area of the rectangle is $403$ square centimeters, what is the width?</p></div>\n</section>"},{"problem_id":"unit06-0127","original_source":"cpm-9-37","source_lesson":"9.1.4","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"5","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 5: Quadratic Modeling","source_type":"Lesson","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Yo-yo motion model interpreted through roots, vertex, and graph features in context.","question_html":"<section class=\"problem\" id=\"9-37\">\n<h2>9-37</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Lesson</span> Sorted to Unit 6, Section 5: Quadratic Modeling</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Models vertical motion with a quadratic equation and interprets intercepts, vertex time, and minimum height.</div>\n<div><p><strong>MOE'S YO-YO</strong></p>\n<p>Moe is playing with a yo-yo. He throws the yo-yo down and then pulls it back up. The motion of the yo-yo is represented by the equation $y=2x^2-4.8x$, where $x$ represents the number of seconds since the yo-yo left Moe's hand, and $y$ represents the vertical height in feet of the yo-yo with respect to Moe's hand. Note that when the yo-yo is in Moe's hand, $y=0$, and when the yo-yo is below his hand, $y$ is negative.</p>\n<ol class=\"lower-alpha\" type=\"a\">\n<li><p>How long is Moe's yo-yo in the air before it comes back to Moe's hand? Write and solve a quadratic equation to find the times that the yo-yo is in Moe's hand.</p></li>\n<li><p>How long does it take for the yo-yo to turn around, that is, to start its return to his hand? Use what you know about parabolas to help you.</p></li>\n<li><p>How long is the yo-yo's string? That is, what is $y$ when the yo-yo changes direction?</p></li>\n<li><p>Draw a sketch of the graph representing the motion of Moe's yo-yo. On the sketch, label the important points: when the yo-yo is in Moe's hand and when it changes direction.</p></li>\n</ol></div>\n</section>"},{"problem_id":"unit06-0128","original_source":"cpm-9-118","source_lesson":"9.4.3","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"5","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 5: Quadratic Modeling","source_type":"Review/Preview","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Selects a system that correctly models a rectangle area situation.","question_html":"<section class=\"problem\" id=\"9-118\">\n<h2>9-118</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Review/Preview</span> Sorted to Unit 6, Section 5: Quadratic Modeling</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Selects a system that models rectangle dimensions using a linear relationship and an area product equation.</div>\n<div>\n<p>Read the following problem. Then decide which system of equations below can represent this situation.</p>\n<p><strong>Multiple Choice:</strong> The length of a rectangle is $4$ units longer than twice its width. If the area is $126$ square units, find the length and width.</p>\n<div class=\"four-col\">\n<div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" type=\"a\"><li><p>$$\\begin{aligned}[t]\n&amp;w = 2l + 4 \\\\\n&amp;wl = 126\n\\end{aligned}$$</p></li></ol></div>\n<div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"2\" type=\"a\"><li><p>$$\\begin{aligned}[t]\n&amp;l = 2w + 4 \\\\\n&amp;l + w = 126\n\\end{aligned}$$</p></li></ol></div>\n<div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"3\" type=\"a\"><li><p>$$\\begin{aligned}[t]\n&amp;w = 2l + 4 \\\\\n&amp;l + w = 126\n\\end{aligned}$$</p></li></ol></div>\n<div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"4\" type=\"a\"><li><p>$$\\begin{aligned}[t]\n&amp;l = 2w + 4 \\\\\n&amp;wl = 126\n\\end{aligned}$$</p></li></ol></div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</section>"},{"problem_id":"unit06-0129","original_source":"cpm-10-41","source_lesson":"10.2.2","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"5","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 5: Quadratic Modeling","source_type":"Review/Preview","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Projectile-height model interpretation.","question_html":"<section class=\"problem\" id=\"10-41\">\n<h2>10-41</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Review/Preview</span> Sorted to Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics, Section 5: Quadratic Modeling</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Interprets a projectile-height quadratic to find landing time and maximum height.</div>\n<p>To avoid a sand trap, a golfer hits a ball so that its height is represented by the equation $h=-16t^2+80t$, where $h$ is the height measured in feet and $t$ is the time measured in seconds. <a class=\"etool-link\" href=\"https://www.desmos.com/calculator/2yr7rrmnc1\" rel=\"noopener\" target=\"_blank\">10-41 HW eTool</a> <span class=\"muted\">(Desmos)</span></p>\n<ol class=\"lower-alpha\" type=\"a\">\n<li>When does the ball land on the ground?</li>\n<li>What is the maximum height of the ball during its flight?</li>\n</ol>\n</section>","resources":[{"label":"10-41 HW eTool","href":"https://www.desmos.com/calculator/2yr7rrmnc1"}]},{"problem_id":"unit06-0130","original_source":"cpm-10-86","source_lesson":"10.2.5","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"5","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 5: Quadratic Modeling","source_type":"Review/Preview","audit_status":"source_only_inferred","notes":"Source-only item not found as a separate row in the uploaded authoritative CSVs; placement inferred from embedded audit text and final rules.","question_html":"<section class=\"problem\" id=\"10-86\">\n<h2>10-86</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Review/Preview</span> Sorted to Unit 6, Section 5: Quadratic Modeling</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Builds a quadratic model from a projectile path with specified zeros and maximum height. Useful eTool link kept.</div>\n<p>Chad is entering a rocket competition. He needs to program his rocket so that when it is launched from the ground, it lands $20$ feet away. In order to qualify, it must be $100$ feet off the ground at its highest point. What equation should he program into his rocket launcher to win? Let $x$ represent the distance from the launch pad in feet and $y$ represent the height of the rocket in feet. Draw a sketch of the rocket\u2019s path. <a class=\"resource\" href=\"https://www.desmos.com/calculator/vl9kbtulon\" rel=\"noopener\" target=\"_blank\">10-86 HW eTool (Desmos)</a></p>\n</section>","resources":[{"label":"10-86 HW eTool (Desmos)","href":"https://www.desmos.com/calculator/vl9kbtulon"}]},{"problem_id":"unit06-0131","original_source":"cpm-10-89","source_lesson":"10.2.6","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"5","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 5: Quadratic Modeling","source_type":"Lesson","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Hot-tub/deck area constraint modeled with a quadratic inequality.","question_html":"<section class=\"problem\" id=\"10-89\">\n<h2>10-89</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Lesson</span> Sorted to Unit 6, Section 5: Quadratic Modeling</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Builds and solves a quadratic inequality from an area constraint involving a square hot tub and a deck on two adjacent sides.</div>\n<p><strong>Rub a Dub Dub</strong></p>\n<p>Ernie is thinking of installing a new hot tub in his backyard. The company he will order it from makes square hot tubs, and the smallest tub he can order is $4$ feet by $4$ feet. He plans to add a $3$-foot-wide deck on two adjacent sides, as shown in the diagram below. If Ernie's backyard, which is also a square, has $169$ square feet of space, what are the possible dimensions that his hot tub can be? Write and solve an inequality that represents this situation. Be sure to define your variable.</p>\n<div class=\"visual-row\">\n<svg aria-label=\"Square hot tub with a three-foot deck on the right side and bottom side.\" class=\"hot-tub-sketch\" role=\"img\" viewbox=\"0 0 260 230\">\n<rect fill=\"#dbeafe\" height=\"120\" stroke=\"#334155\" stroke-width=\"3\" width=\"120\" x=\"50\" y=\"30\"></rect>\n<rect fill=\"#fef3c7\" height=\"165\" stroke=\"#334155\" stroke-width=\"3\" width=\"45\" x=\"170\" y=\"30\"></rect>\n<rect fill=\"#fef3c7\" height=\"45\" stroke=\"#334155\" stroke-width=\"3\" width=\"165\" x=\"50\" y=\"150\"></rect>\n<line stroke=\"#334155\" stroke-width=\"3\" x1=\"170\" x2=\"170\" y1=\"30\" y2=\"195\"></line>\n<line stroke=\"#334155\" stroke-width=\"3\" x1=\"50\" x2=\"215\" y1=\"150\" y2=\"150\"></line>\n<text font-family=\"Arial\" font-size=\"18\" text-anchor=\"middle\" x=\"110\" y=\"96\">Hot Tub</text>\n<text font-family=\"Arial\" font-size=\"16\" text-anchor=\"middle\" transform=\"rotate(90 190 115)\" x=\"190\" y=\"115\">Deck</text>\n<text font-family=\"Arial\" font-size=\"16\" text-anchor=\"middle\" x=\"132\" y=\"180\">Deck</text>\n<line stroke=\"#334155\" stroke-width=\"2\" x1=\"170\" x2=\"215\" y1=\"18\" y2=\"18\"></line>\n<line stroke=\"#334155\" stroke-width=\"2\" x1=\"170\" x2=\"170\" y1=\"13\" y2=\"23\"></line>\n<line stroke=\"#334155\" stroke-width=\"2\" x1=\"215\" x2=\"215\" y1=\"13\" y2=\"23\"></line>\n<text font-family=\"Arial\" font-size=\"14\" text-anchor=\"middle\" x=\"192\" y=\"12\">3 ft</text>\n<line stroke=\"#334155\" stroke-width=\"2\" x1=\"228\" x2=\"228\" y1=\"150\" y2=\"195\"></line>\n<line stroke=\"#334155\" stroke-width=\"2\" x1=\"223\" x2=\"233\" y1=\"150\" y2=\"150\"></line>\n<line stroke=\"#334155\" stroke-width=\"2\" x1=\"223\" x2=\"233\" y1=\"195\" y2=\"195\"></line>\n<text font-family=\"Arial\" font-size=\"14\" text-anchor=\"middle\" transform=\"rotate(90 247 176)\" x=\"247\" y=\"176\">3 ft</text>\n</svg>\n</div>\n</section>"},{"problem_id":"unit06-0132","original_source":"cpm-10-133","source_lesson":"10.3.3","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"5","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 5: Quadratic Modeling","source_type":"Lesson","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Projectile-height context modeled with a quadratic inequality.","question_html":"<section class=\"problem\" id=\"10-133\">\n<h2>10-133</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Lesson</span> Sorted to Unit 6, Section 5: Quadratic Modeling</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Models a projectile-height context with a quadratic inequality and asks for a time interval solution.</div>\n<p>San Francisco is well known for its fog: very thick, low-lying clouds that hide its hills. One foggy day, Penelope was practicing kicking a football on the football field of her school. Once she kicked the football so high that it disappeared into the fog.</p>\n<p>If the height $h$ of the ball, in feet, could be represented at time $t$, in seconds, by the equation $h=-16t^2+96t$, and if the fog was $140$ feet off the ground, during what times of its flight was the ball not visible? Explain how you got your answer. Represent your solution algebraically and on a number line.</p>\n</section>"},{"problem_id":"unit06-0133","original_source":"cpm-11-104","source_lesson":"11.3.4","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"5","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 5: Quadratic Modeling","source_type":"Lesson","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Maximum-area fencing investigation using multiple representations and optimization.","question_html":"<section class=\"problem\" id=\"11-104\">\n<h2>11-104</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Lesson</span> Sorted to Unit 6, Section 5: Quadratic Modeling</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Models a maximum-area fencing situation with a quadratic relationship; keeps the useful CPM Student eTool link. | Images: figures/11-104.png</div>\n<p><strong>FENCING LESSONS</strong></p>\n<p>Lucy wants to be a farmer, just like her dad. Her father says he will give her some cows to raise if she can build them a good pen. Lucy saves her money and buys $30$ meters of fencing material. She will use it to build a rectangular pen against one wall of her family's barn, as shown in the picture.</p>\n<div class=\"visual-row\"><img alt=\"Rectangular pen built against a barn wall, with the two side lengths labeled x and the front width labeled 30 minus 2x.\" class=\"figure medium\" src=\"assets/11-104.png\"/></div>\n<p>Lucy has come to you for help. She wants to build a pen for her cows that gives them as much area to roam in as possible. How long should each side of the fence be to give the cows as much roaming area as possible? How can you convince Lucy that this pen is the largest? Explore this using the <a class=\"resource\" href=\"https://technology.cpm.org/general/tiles/?tiledata=ahCCA%2011-104%20Student%20eTool%20__11-104.%20FENCING%20LESSONS%0A%0ALucy%20wants%20to%20be%20a%20farmer%2C%20just%20like%20her%20dad.%20%20Her%20father%20says%20he%20will%20give%20her%20some%20cows%20to%20raise%20if%20she%20can%20build%20them%20a%20good%20pen.%20%20Lucy%20saves%20her%20money%20and%20buys%2030%20meters%20of%20fencing%20material.%20%20She%20will%20use%20it%20to%20build%20a%20rectangular%20pen%20against%20one%20wall%20of%20her%20family%E2%80%99s%20barn%2C%20as%20shown%20in%20the%20picture%20at%20right.%0A%0ALucy%20has%20come%20to%20you%20for%20help.%20%20She%20wants%20to%20build%20a%20pen%20for%20her%20cows%20that%20gives%20them%20the%20most%20possible%20area%20to%20roam.%20%20How%20long%20should%20each%20side%20of%20the%20fence%20be%20to%20give%20the%20cows%20as%20much%20roaming%20area%20as%20possible%3F%20%20How%20can%20you%20convince%20Lucy%20that%20the%20pen%20you%20suggest%20has%20the%20largest%20roaming%20area%3F%0A%0AYour%20Task%3A%0A%0A%E2%80%A2%20Create%20a%20poster%20showing%20all%20four%20representations%20of%20this%20situation.%0A%0A%E2%80%A2%20On%20your%20poster%2C%20include%20a%20drawing%20of%20the%20pen%20with%20the%20largest%20possible%20area.%20%20State%20its%20dimensions%20(width%20and%20length)%20and%20its%20area.%0A%0A%E2%80%A2%20Use%20multiple%20representations%20to%20justify%20your%20conclusion%20that%20this%20is%20the%20largest%20pen.__fXa2x__boy__aebkJpkpQhFBarn__t3qj\" rel=\"noopener\" target=\"_blank\">11-104 Student eTool</a>.</p>\n<p><strong>Your Task:</strong></p><ul><li>Create a poster showing all four representations: graph, table, equation, and situation.</li><li>On your poster, include a drawing of the pen with the largest possible area. State its dimensions, width and height, and its area.</li><li>Use multiple representations to justify your conclusion that this is the largest pen.</li></ul>\n</section>","resources":[{"label":"11-104 Student eTool","href":"https://technology.cpm.org/general/tiles/?tiledata=ahCCA%2011-104%20Student%20eTool%20__11-104.%20FENCING%20LESSONS%0A%0ALucy%20wants%20to%20be%20a%20farmer%2C%20just%20like%20her%20dad.%20%20Her%20father%20says%20he%20will%20give%20her%20some%20cows%20to%20raise%20if%20she%20can%20build%20them%20a%20good%20pen.%20%20Lucy%20saves%20her%20money%20and%20buys%2030%20meters%20of%20fencing%20material.%20%20She%20will%20use%20it%20to%20build%20a%20rectangular%20pen%20against%20one%20wall%20of%20her%20family%E2%80%99s%20barn%2C%20as%20shown%20in%20the%20picture%20at%20right.%0A%0ALucy%20has%20come%20to%20you%20for%20help.%20%20She%20wants%20to%20build%20a%20pen%20for%20her%20cows%20that%20gives%20them%20the%20most%20possible%20area%20to%20roam.%20%20How%20long%20should%20each%20side%20of%20the%20fence%20be%20to%20give%20the%20cows%20as%20much%20roaming%20area%20as%20possible%3F%20%20How%20can%20you%20convince%20Lucy%20that%20the%20pen%20you%20suggest%20has%20the%20largest%20roaming%20area%3F%0A%0AYour%20Task%3A%0A%0A%E2%80%A2%20Create%20a%20poster%20showing%20all%20four%20representations%20of%20this%20situation.%0A%0A%E2%80%A2%20On%20your%20poster%2C%20include%20a%20drawing%20of%20the%20pen%20with%20the%20largest%20possible%20area.%20%20State%20its%20dimensions%20(width%20and%20length)%20and%20its%20area.%0A%0A%E2%80%A2%20Use%20multiple%20representations%20to%20justify%20your%20conclusion%20that%20this%20is%20the%20largest%20pen.__fXa2x__boy__aebkJpkpQhFBarn__t3qj"}]},{"problem_id":"unit06-0134","original_source":"cpm-11-105","source_lesson":"11.3.4","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"5","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 5: Quadratic Modeling","source_type":"Lesson","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Creates a table of dimensions and areas to investigate maximum area.","question_html":"<section class=\"problem\" id=\"11-105\">\n<h2>11-105</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Further Guidance</span> Sorted to Unit 6, Section 5: Quadratic Modeling</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Builds a table of possible dimensions and areas for the maximum-area fencing model.</div>\n<p><strong>MAKING A TABLE</strong></p><p>Start by trying out some different-sized pens to see which ones appear to give the largest area. Your teacher will show you how to use string to make models of possible pens.</p><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" type=\"a\"><li>Start an $x \\to y$ table for this situation. Let $x$ represent the length of the sides of the pen that are attached to the barn and let $y$ represent the enclosed area. Use your string model to try out at least four other sets of pen dimensions. Calculate the area for each pen you try and enter your data into your table.</li><li>Of all the pens you have tried so far, which dimensions have created the largest possible roaming area for the cows? Do you think this is the largest area possible? Why or why not?</li></ol>\n</section>"},{"problem_id":"unit06-0135","original_source":"cpm-11-106","source_lesson":"11.3.4","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"5","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 5: Quadratic Modeling","source_type":"Lesson","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Graphs area data and interprets intercepts in context.","question_html":"<section class=\"problem\" id=\"11-106\">\n<h2>11-106</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Further Guidance</span> Sorted to Unit 6, Section 5: Quadratic Modeling</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Graphs the table data, considers feasible intercepts, and connects intercepts to the physical context.</div>\n<p><strong>MAKING A GRAPH</strong></p><p>A graph can help you analyze the data.</p><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" type=\"a\"><li>Graph the data from problem 11-105. Be careful about how you scale your axes, so that all the possible pens will fit on your graph.</li><li>Is there a point on the graph where $x$ is almost as big as it can possibly be? Do you have a point on your graph where $x$ is almost as small as it can possibly be? If you are missing pens like these, build an example of each one using your string, enter the lengths and areas in your table, and plot the points on your graph.</li><li>Should the $x$-intercepts be included on your graph? Discuss this with your team and justify your conclusions. What do the $x$-intercepts of this graph represent?</li></ol>\n</section>"},{"problem_id":"unit06-0136","original_source":"cpm-11-107","source_lesson":"11.3.4","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"5","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 5: Quadratic Modeling","source_type":"Lesson","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Uses the graph to approximate maximum area and dimensions.","question_html":"<section class=\"problem\" id=\"11-107\">\n<h2>11-107</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Further Guidance</span> Sorted to Unit 6, Section 5: Quadratic Modeling</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Uses the graph of a quadratic area model to approximate the maximum and corresponding dimensions.</div>\n<p><strong>ANALYZING THE GRAPH</strong></p><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" type=\"a\"><li>Looking at the points you have plotted so far, can you see what the general shape of the graph will be? If so, sketch what you think the whole graph should look like. If not, build some more pens with your string to fill in the sections of the graph where you do not have enough points. When you see the general shape of the graph, sketch it.</li><li>Find the point on your graph representing the pen with the greatest area. What are the dimensions of this pen?</li><li>Use your graph to approximate the greatest possible enclosed area.</li></ol>\n</section>"},{"problem_id":"unit06-0137","original_source":"cpm-11-108","source_lesson":"11.3.4","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"5","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 5: Quadratic Modeling","source_type":"Lesson","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Develops the quadratic model algebraically and uses roots and vertex to determine the exact maximum.","question_html":"<section class=\"problem\" id=\"11-108\">\n<h2>11-108</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Further Guidance</span> Sorted to Unit 6, Section 5: Quadratic Modeling</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Writes and analyzes the quadratic area equation, including roots and vertex, to find an exact maximum.</div>\n<p><strong>WRITING AN EQUATION</strong></p><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" type=\"a\"><li>If the length of the sides that are attached to the barn are $x$ meters long, and if she has only $30$ meters of barbed wire, write an expression for the width of the pen in terms of $x$.</li><li>Now write an equation for $y$, the area of the space enclosed by the fence, in terms of $x$. Simplify your equation.</li><li>What kind of graph should this equation have? Does it match your graph?</li><li>In your equation from part (b), set $y=0$ and find the roots of the resulting equation. Does your graph confirm these roots?</li><li>Use your equation to find the vertex of the graph. Does your graph confirm this result?</li><li>Use your new results to find the largest possible roaming area Lucy can give her cows. What are the dimensions of this pen? Is this answer more precise than the one you got from your graph? How do you know?</li></ol>\n</section>"},{"problem_id":"unit06-0138","original_source":"cpm-11-109","source_lesson":"11.3.4","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"5","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 5: Quadratic Modeling","source_type":"Lesson","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Synthesizes table, graph, equation, and context into a complete optimization argument.","question_html":"<section class=\"problem\" id=\"11-109\">\n<h2>11-109</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Further Guidance</span> Sorted to Unit 6, Section 5: Quadratic Modeling</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Synthesizes all four representations to justify a maximum-area quadratic modeling conclusion.</div>\n<p><strong>SHOWING YOUR WORK</strong></p><p>Finally, put together a poster showing your work for this problem. Be sure to include all four representations of the situation. Use the equation and the graph to justify to Lucy which dimensions the pen should have.</p>\n</section>"},{"problem_id":"unit06-0139","original_source":"cpm-11-130","source_lesson":"11.3.5","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"5","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 5: Quadratic Modeling","source_type":"Review/Preview","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Interprets a profit model and uses the vertex to maximize profit.","question_html":"<section class=\"problem\" id=\"11-130\">\n<h2>11-130</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Review/Preview</span> Sorted to Unit 6, Section 5: Quadratic Modeling</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Interprets the vertex of a quadratic profit model in context; kept the useful Desmos HW eTool link.</div>\n<p>The profit made by ACME Home Construction is represented by the function $y=-x^2+50x$ where $x=$ the number of homes built and $y=$ the profit in thousands of dollars. How many homes should be built to maximize the profit? Hint: Think about the graph of the function. <a class=\"resource\" href=\"https://www.desmos.com/calculator/clyv4w94bz\" rel=\"noopener\" target=\"_blank\">11-130 HW eTool</a></p>\n</section>","resources":[{"label":"11-130 HW eTool","href":"https://www.desmos.com/calculator/clyv4w94bz"}]},{"problem_id":"unit06-0140","original_source":"cpm-CP11-13","source_lesson":"Checkpoint 11","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"5","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 5: Quadratic Modeling","source_type":"Checkpoint","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Contextual quadratic model; interpret zeros, maximum/minimum, or optimization meaning.","question_html":"<section class=\"problem\" id=\"CP11-13\"><h2>CP11-13</h2><div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Checkpoint 11</span> The Quadratic Web</div><div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Solve a quadratic projectile model for ground time and maximum height.</div>\n<p class=\"directions\">Solve the quadratic model.</p>\n<div class=\"prompt\">A path of a golf ball is given by $h=-16t^2+80t$, where $h$ is the height of the ball in feet and $t$ is the time in seconds. When does the ball hit the ground and what is the maximum height of the ball?</div>\n<div class=\"workspace\" style=\"min-height:120px;\"></div>\n</section>"},{"problem_id":"unit06-0141","original_source":"cpm-CP11-14","source_lesson":"Checkpoint 11","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"5","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 5: Quadratic Modeling","source_type":"Checkpoint","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Contextual quadratic model; interpret zeros, maximum/minimum, or optimization meaning.","question_html":"<section class=\"problem\" id=\"CP11-14\"><h2>CP11-14</h2><div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Checkpoint 11</span> The Quadratic Web</div><div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Solve a quadratic rocket model for ground location and maximum height.</div>\n<p class=\"directions\">Solve the quadratic model.</p>\n<div class=\"prompt\">Amelia launched her science fair rocket and then backed away. The path of the rocket is given by $h=-10x^2+100x-160$, where $h$ is the height in feet and $x$ is the distance in feet from Amelia. Where does the rocket hit the ground and what is the maximum height of the rocket?</div>\n<div class=\"workspace\" style=\"min-height:120px;\"></div>\n</section>"},{"problem_id":"unit06-0142","original_source":"cpm-CP11-15","source_lesson":"Checkpoint 11","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"5","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 5: Quadratic Modeling","source_type":"Checkpoint","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Contextual quadratic model; interpret zeros, maximum/minimum, or optimization meaning.","question_html":"<section class=\"problem\" id=\"CP11-15\"><h2>CP11-15</h2><div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Checkpoint 11</span> The Quadratic Web</div><div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Use the vertex of a quadratic revenue model to maximize revenue.</div>\n<p class=\"directions\">Solve the quadratic model.</p>\n<div class=\"prompt\">The revenue of a company is given by $R=-1.5x^2+30x$, where $R$ is the revenue in millions and $x$ is the number of units made in thousands. How many units should be made to maximize revenue?</div>\n<div class=\"workspace\" style=\"min-height:120px;\"></div>\n</section>"},{"problem_id":"unit06-0143","original_source":"cpm-CP11-16","source_lesson":"Checkpoint 11","category":"Unit 6: Solving and Modeling with Quadratics","section":"5","unit_section_title":"Unit 6, Section 5: Quadratic Modeling","source_type":"Checkpoint","audit_status":"authoritative","notes":"Contextual quadratic model; interpret zeros, maximum/minimum, or optimization meaning.","question_html":"<section class=\"problem\" id=\"CP11-16\"><h2>CP11-16</h2><div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Checkpoint 11</span> The Quadratic Web</div><div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Use the vertex of a quadratic profit model to maximize profit.</div>\n<p class=\"directions\">Solve the quadratic model.</p>\n<div class=\"prompt\">The profit of a company is given by $P=-x^2+130x-3000$. If $P$ is the profit in millions and $x$ is the number of items produced in millions, what number of items should be produced to maximize profit?</div>\n<div class=\"workspace\" style=\"min-height:120px;\"></div>\n</section>"}];